\par\par \b \uc2 A better  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2  with tougher social problems   \b0\par\par\uc2 Umar Juoro , Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,092 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 December 2006\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2006 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Even though the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was quite tough in early 2006, as shown by the high inflation and low growth, at the end of the year the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  picked up as inflation went down significantly. The improvements in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will likely continue as we enter 2007. Low inflation, followed by low \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the starting up of infrastructure projects, at least on a selected basis, will create a better environment for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow.   \par \par \uc2 Growth of 6 percent or higher is reachable in 2007, as the government has forecast, if the infrastructure projects run well and the roadblocks to investment are overcome.   \par \par \uc2 With better macroeconomic conditions, the banking sector will be able to allocated more loans to various business activities and consumers. As the banks allocate more loans to consumers, particularly for house purchases, the construction sector, especially housing development, will benefit.   \par \par \uc2 Also, lower inflation and lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will increase the purchasing power of consumers. This will lead to higher growth in the retail trade sector.   \par \par \uc2 The telecommunications sector will remain the star in terms of growth as the number of wireless telephone subscribers continues to grow. Investment in this sector is also substantial, as different from other infrastructure projects, the telecommunications sector does not face serious problems in terms of land acquisition and government guarantees.   \par \par \uc2 However, the manufacturing and mining sectors will continue to face low growth. The manufacturing sector still has the problem of high production costs and weak demand, except probably the automotive sector, including motorcycles, which will benefit from the expansion in bank lending.   \par \par \uc2 The mining and oil and gas sectors still face structural problems in terms of a lack of incentive and cumbersome regulations. This, of course, does not apply to companies that currently operate optimally and are taking advantage of high commodity prices. The issue is the lack of new investment on a large scale.   \par \par \uc2 Agricultural growth is traditionally low, although plantation crops, such as palm oil and rubber, are benefiting from high commodity prices. The issue of managing rice prices will remain the hot issue in \b \highlight22\uc2 public policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as rice imports are needed to stabilize prices, while local governments and lobbies protest such imports.   \par \par \uc2 From the \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  side, household consumption growth will resume although not fully recover from the decline in purchasing power since the fuel price increases in October 2005. The lower inflation and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  encourage consumers to spend more. This is in line with higher growth in the retail, automotive and housing sectors.   \par \par \uc2 Exports will likely perform relatively well on the back of higher prices of commodities and selected manufactured products, such as textiles, garments and electronics, despite the tough competition from China. However, the issue of the inflexibility of the labor law will continue to discourage production and expansion in this sector. Meanwhile, imports will likely pick up both in the category of intermediate and consumer goods. Many companies have started to expand production so that there is higher demand for imported intermediate goods. Similarly, there will be higher demand for imported consumer products among consumers with higher incomes.   \par \par \uc2 However, investment might still face the serious problem of structural issues, especially regulations at the national as well as local levels. The government has claimed success in implementing its investment \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  package. However, the most important laws that the government promised to enact, namely the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and investment laws, remain \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while the planned revision of the labor law has been annulled.   \par \par \uc2 The revisions of the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  laws has been delayed for political reason. The PDI-P faction at the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  has opposed the revisions in an effort to score political points. Meanwhile, the Golkar faction is likely to wait and see whether the President accommodates its interests with more seats in the Cabinet before they decide whether to support the revisions.   \par \par \uc2 The investment bill is too broad and is considered too liberal by several factions at the House.   \par \par \uc2 The government also promised to facilitate investment under the concept of special \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  zones, starting with Batam, Bintan and Karimun. Steps such as improving investment procedures through one-stop service and one document for customs have been implemented, but these are still far from sufficient to woo new investment as many opaque procedures essentially remain the same.   \par \par \uc2 Furthermore, \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and other incentives will likely be postponed as they are incorporated into the revisions of the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and investment laws. It is also unclear as to whether the government will propose a law on special \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  zones.   \par \par \uc2 Selected infrastructure projects, such as power plants and toll roads, will start to be implemented in 2007. The government seems willing to give guarantees for power plant projects. Nevertheless, the government has yet to do so for fear of the implications later on, especially related to the completion of the projects and accountability matters. In addition, the issue of land acquisition remains a serious hurdle for toll road projects.   \par \par \uc2 Unemployment is a serious social issue. A moderate growth level of 6 percent is not high enough to absorb all the new people entering the labor force. The deadlock over the labor law revision will further discourage companies from hiring more workers.   \par \par \uc2 This certainly will create the more serious issue of a widening social gap between the haves and the have nots. As the rich enjoy better opportunities with the lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and selected opportunities in business to get higher returns, the poor will still face serious problems of unemployment and poverty. This certainly will test the popularity of President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, which is still high.   \par \par \uc2 The government itself has been acting seriously to allocate more money for programs that address the unemployment and poverty problems. However, the relatively low capacity of national and especially local governments to implement the programs, as shown by the slow pace of capital \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  of capital expenditures, will make these poverty-alleviation programs less effective.   \par \par \uc2 The challenge in general remains the same, except in a better macroeconomic environment. The environment for investment has not been improved significantly. As a consequence many business opportunities are not being utilized optimally. \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is mainly supported by better macroeconomic conditions, which have led to higher confidence among consumers and businesses. More fundamental improvements in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will depend on the ability of the government to overcome the major hurdles to investment.<br>   \par \par \uc2 The writer is chairman of the Center for Information and Development Studies (CIDES) and a senior fellow at the Habibie Center. This is a personal view.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020061230e2cu00018\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
