\par\par \b \uc2 Bad omen?  \b0\par\par\uc2 Major transportation disasters marked the turn of year from 2006 to 2007. An Adam Air plane carrying 96 passengers apparently crashed Monday. Only three days earlier, a passenger ferry sank in the Java Sea; 400 passengers are dead or missing.  \par \uc2 624 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 January 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 To pessimists or critics, the two accidents may be seen as a bad omen for both the Yudhoyono administration and the nation, which have gone through a difficult year plagued by man-made and natural disasters. Thousands were killed, and millions of others put at risk of poverty due to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impacts of the calamities.  \par \par \uc2 The reported plane crash came just after President Yudhoyono made a wish in a New Year's prayer that the nation would be spared from disasters and national disintegration. People from all walks of life share that hope, as Indonesia has been experiencing a flurry of catastrophes since the Aceh tsunami tragedy in December 2004. The plight has dragged on for many of the disaster victims as they have not received adequate assistance. Thousands are still camping in makeshift tents in Aceh and Yogyakarta. Many more in Sidoarjo are facing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about whether their demand for compensation for their properties flooded by hot mud will be met.  \par \par \uc2 Not only have those calamities cost the country trillions of rupiahs in material losses, but they have played havoc with its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development programs.  \par \par \uc2 Whether or not the transportation disasters augur bad luck for the country in 2007, it is generally accepted that such accidents can be prevented with good technology.  \par \par \uc2 The Meteorology and Geophysics Agency releases its weather forecasts on a daily basis. Poor weather therefore cannot provide an excuse for the fatal mishaps, and a government ban on flying during bad weather following the Adam Air accident is just too late. The bulk of the problems may rest with how weather alerts are distributed to relevant government institutions and transportation operators, and how they respond.  \par \par \uc2 With the investigation still underway, it is too early to accuse the management of Adam Air and the operator of the Senopati Nusantara ferry of ignoring weather forecasts or safety rules. The National Transportation Safety Commission, however, should explore this possibility and regularly scrutinize all transportation companies to make sure they comply with the rules.  \par \par \uc2 This scrutiny is necessary to prevent low cost transportation operators from compromising safety by cutting the maintenance \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  or other safety-related expenditures. Accidents involving \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  airlines took place quite often last year, raising doubts about the companies' commitment to safety. As Vice President Jusuf Kalla put it, the accidents could erode the companies' image amid the tight competition in the airline business.  \par \par \uc2 Following an inspection in the wake of the Mandala plane crash which killed at least 149 people, including 47 on the ground, in Medan, North Sumatra in September 2005, the government grounded several commercial planes for failing to meet safety standards. Last July, the government banned the operation of around 50 Boeing 737-200s, days after a plane belonging to low-cost Batavia Air skidded off the runway due to a leak in its hydraulic system.  \par \par \uc2 All of these measures came only after a problem occurred, even though accidents involving airplanes or other modes of transportation are basically preventable.  \par \par \uc2 The establishment and implementation of civil aviation safety rules and navigation aids in the United States has curbed the fatal accident rate from about 1 for every 1,000,000 miles flown in 1929 to no more than 2 per every 2,000,000,000 miles flown since 1997. The rules have made air travel one of the safest modes of transportation.  \par \par \uc2 We cannot delay taking action to reduce casualties. The government's failure to take precautionary measures is perhaps, in itself, the bad omen.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070103e3130000i\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
