\par\par \b \uc2 RI must improve investment climate: German businesses   \b0\par\par\uc2 Sascha Zastiral , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 808 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 January 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 For decades political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations between Indonesia and Germany have been cordial and solid. After examining their recent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  relationship, however, one may ask whether relations are as sweet as they once were.   \par \par \uc2 Germany is Europe's largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and its trade with nations such as Singapore, Malaysia and Thailand has surged in recent years. However, trade with Indonesia, Southeast Asia's largest market, is exhibiting a downward trend.   \par \par \uc2 Trade figures between Germany and Indonesia are discouraging. Bilateral trade in the first eight months of 2006 (from January to August) amounted to only US$2.22 billion, a 6.71 percent drop from the 2005 total of $2.38 billion during the same period.   \par \par \uc2 This figure seems diminutive when compared with bilateral trade between Indonesia and Japan, which amounted to $17.46 billion between January and August 2006.   \par \par \uc2 These trends have likewise been reflected in investment figures between the two nations. Germany slipped from 15th down to 23rd with regards to the size of its Indonesian investments, which amounted to just over $18.3 million in 2005.   \par \par \uc2 This qualifies Germany as a minor trading partner of Indonesia, and the European nation of over 80 million people is now far behind smaller nations such as Taiwan and Thailand.   \par \par \uc2 This is despite the prevalence of foundations that should ensure a sound trading relationship with Indonesia. Around 200 German companies are already based in the archipelago, many of which have their own production facilities.   \par \par \uc2 Added to this, there are a number of long-lasting treaties between the nations. Indonesia and Germany signed an agreement in 1968 over the protection of capital investment. Likewise, in 1977 they signed an agreement against double \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 But these measures proved insufficient. German businesses say the Indonesian government must improve the nation's investment climate.   \par \par \uc2 "Many of our members claim that it takes too long and is very costly to get investment permission from the Indonesian side," says Barliana Amir, a spokesperson for the German-Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia promised to adjust its laws in order to encourage foreign investments, though this promise has not yet been carried through. As a result, German investors continue to cite a degree of legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 "The basic requirements for investments haven't been set up yet so as to attract more German multinationals," a German business interest group insider says.   \par \par \uc2 "I suppose when this is fixed, things will start going."   \par \par \uc2 Despite the declining nature of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations between the two nations, German-Indonesian cooperation in other fields is proving successful.   \par \par \uc2 One such example has been Germany's involvement in the Aceh peace process.   \par \par \uc2 "But the peace process is not over, it has only just begun," says Germany's Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development, Wieczorek-Zeul, who recently visited Banda Aceh and Jakarta. Now, support for employment and microfinance programs are of huge importance, she says.   \par \par \uc2 The Aceh initiative reflects Germany's strong conviction that social unrest and political and religious radicalization can only be prevented by development, the German minister says.   \par \par \uc2 "We observe very closely where Indonesia, the country with the largest Muslim population in the world, is going," she says.   \par \par \uc2 Owing to this conviction, Germany has become one of Aceh's most generous emergency aid contributors following the 2004 tsunami.   \par \par \uc2 Following from this, in December, Indonesia and Germany signed their fourth debt swap agreement, which will see Germany increase aid in 2006 by 20 million euros. German aid now stands at 250 million euros.   \par \par \uc2 Indeed, there is a long history of German development projects in Indonesia, the first of which began in 1950. Currently, it is the second biggest development program contributor after Japan, with donations standing at around $3 billion.   \par \par \uc2 Germany is also playing a crucial role in developing and installing a disaster warning system that aims to prevent high death figures in the future. It is called the German-Indonesian Tsunami Early Warning System, and is being developed by the Institute for Geosciences in Potsdam, near Berlin.   \par \par \uc2 Despite the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  climate, some German firms have been expanding their presence in the country.   \par \par \uc2 Multinationals such as Heidelberg Cement, Allianz, Bayer and Beiersdorf have fortified their \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  strongholds during the last few years.   \par \par \uc2 Germany has also stepped up its defense trade with Indonesia. For the first time in 14 years the German government delivered a number of MP5 machine guns to presidential guards. Indonesia is also considering buying two kilo-class attack submarines from Germany.   \par \par \uc2 Will these events boost \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ties between the two countries?   \par \par \uc2 "There seems to be no link between development programs and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations," Barliana Amir says. "I think that many German companies will wait to see the progress made by the Indonesian government.   \par \par \uc2 "If the government keeps to their promise, everything will improve."   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070108e3180000y\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
