\par\par \b \uc2 The direction of Indonesia in 2007  \b0\par\par\uc2 The direction of Indonesia in 2007  \par \uc2 1,303 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 January 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Michael Vatikiotis , Singapore  \par \par \uc2 2. Mediation and peace building  \par \par \uc2 The Aceh peace deal was a significant turning point for Indonesia in the eyes of the international community. Just three years earlier, Indonesia was cast as the brutal colonial power leaving East Timor in flames to an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  future as a newly independent nation. In Aceh, notwithstanding the continued clamor for effective autonomy in Papua, Indonesia was able to show the world that internal conflict can be resolved peacefully.  \par \par \uc2 The speed with which autonomy was granted, arms were surrendered and now elections have been held -- and won by a member of the former rebel group -- has helped mask many unresolved issues like human rights abuses and the fate of many thousands of missing Acehnese during periods of martial law. The emphasis has been on resolution rather than reconciliation, the hope being that one will eventually lead to the other.  \par \par \uc2 Unspoken of course is the contrast between effective peaceful resolution in autonomous Aceh and continued conflict in independent East Timor. Rather than highlight this awkward reality, Indonesian officials prefer to stress the lessons of the Aceh peace deal, which they would argue have vindicated the legislated autonomy approach, and demonstrated the way that international mediation and monitoring can help pave the way for a successful solution that preserves national sovereignty.  \par \par \uc2 Don't be surprised therefore to see Indonesia touting itself as a mediator in regional and international conflicts espousing the Aceh model. Indonesia's participation in the United Nations peacekeeping force in Lebanon is one sign of this; now there is a confident willingness to offer help in Iraq.  \par \par \uc2 3. Islam and religiosity  \par \par \uc2 The 2002 Bali bombings opened a new front in the global war on terror and threatened to brand Indonesia a rogue state. Initially the crisis was handled badly. Indonesia wanted evidence it could prove in court that Islamic militants were connected with al-Qaeda; it baulked at the idea of tough security laws. Understandably, the government was worried about a backlash from Islamic quarters in a newly democratic setting. There were testy exchanges with U.S. and Australian officials about the hypocrisy of policies that urged suspending due legal process in the interests of somebody else's security.  \par \par \uc2 In the end, the government's insistence on using legal channels, combined with solid police work in cooperation with the international community, paid off. A small number of dangerous militants have either been arrested or their movements and activity greatly constrained.  \par \par \uc2 But JI was always the tip of a much larger iceberg. A far more ominous development in the minds of many Indonesians has been the gradual growth of Muslim religiosity over the past two decades and the impact this is said to be having on the social and political landscape. The roots of this Islamic resurgence lie in the growing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  divide in Indonesia and the extent to which ordinary people feel that the only escape from unrelenting poverty, corruption and moral degradation is their religious faith.  \par \par \uc2 Forty years ago some of these same factors drove millions of Indonesians into the arms of the Communist Party. But Socialism has lost its appeal and relevance in the Post Cold War era, which leaves the mosque, the church and the temple as the only avenue for salvation in this world, as well as the next.  \par \par \uc2 Mainstream anxiety is focused on the growing appeal of conservative Islamic government at the district level. In the past two years, the number of districts in Indonesia that have voted in favor of rule under sharia law has doubled from twelve to twenty-four. Indonesian Muslim scholar Sya'fiie Anwar describes what he terms the gradual sharia-ization of Indonesia. There have been \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  floggings in Aceh and several cases of women being arrested for simply walking home from work. But is an apocalyptic scenario justified?  \par \par \uc2 Let's examine what Indonesia is not afflicted by. The growing Shiite-Sunni divide that is setting the Middle East on fire is not relevant in Indonesia, where the vast majority of Muslims subscribe to mainstream Sunni Islam. In all there are said to be no more than 100,000 Shiites in Indonesia. Religious freedom is guaranteed constitutionally. More specifically, the question of sharia law has been settled at the national level by a vote in the assembly rejecting its incorporation in the national constitution.  \par \par \uc2 Now turn around and look at the rest of the Muslim world. In Bangladesh and Pakistan militant Islamic organization have a greater influence in politics and threaten regime stability. In India, there are serious tensions between Muslim and Hindu communities in Gujarat. In Egypt and Jordan, the Muslim Brotherhood is garnering support in grass roots communities who feel they are marginalized by the current regimes.  \par \par \uc2 In Lebanon and the Palestinian territories, populist Muslim brotherhood and Shiite militant movements are draw support at the ballot box and from across the Arab world. And then there is Iraq. Which part of this fractured, violent picture does Indonesia fit into? Contrary to alarmist reports that often project Indonesia on the verge of being taken over by Islamic fundamentalists, the world's largest Muslim community continues to live in harmony with non-Muslims, adheres to democratic values, and sets a shining example for the rest of the Muslim world.  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia now needs to turn the perception tables around and start projecting its own social and political success story onto the rest of the Muslim world. It must show that religiosity and violence don't necessarily go hand in hand and that democracy is compatible with Islam. Indonesia must also be confident enough to use these vital credentials to engage with all the parties involved in the Middle East conflict.  \par \par \uc2 In fact, President Yudhoyono has made engagement in the Middle East conflict a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  priority. He has even offered to help the U.S. disengage from Iraq by proposing to help frame a reconciliation plan with the help of the Muslim world. These are encouraging signals and the international community can help by taking them seriously. By doing so, Indonesia will be contributing constructively to larger problems in the wider Muslim world.  \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's long journey from political torpidity, to turbulence and transition has resulted in the country's emergence as a stable democracy and moderate Muslim nation in a world that sees these qualities as incompatible. The rest of ASEAN has yet to wake up to these changes, in part because of the poor capacity of Indonesian officialdom to project its voice -- as well as a familiar reluctance to impose its views on the region. This is changing.  \par \par \uc2 President Yudhoyono has made it clear that he intends to pursue an active foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and one that incorporates the country's democratic, cultural and social values. We can expect Indonesia to strongly support the incorporation of universal human rights and democratic values into the ASEAN charter. We can expect more pressure on Myanmar to pursue a democratic course, especially now that Indonesia is a member of the UN Security Council. And we can certainly expect Indonesia to insert itself more actively into the Middle East conflict, where the current impasse would appear to require fresh approaches.  \par \par \uc2 In short, despite the obvious need to focus on shortcomings at home, Indonesia's long history of activism and idealism on the international stage make it likely that many of the more positive aspects of Indonesia's democratic transition will be injected into foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The world would do well to take Indonesia seriously, because it is perhaps one of the few rising medium-sized powers in this world that can be said, at least for now, to have good intentions.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is a visiting research fellow at the Institute of Southeast Asian Studies in Singapore.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070110e31a0000r\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
