\par\par \b \uc2 Higher bank lending a pipe dream without  \highlight22\uc2 policy \highlight\uc2  and legal certainty   \b0\par\par\uc2 Ari Pitoyo, CFA , Head of Research   \par \uc2 881 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 January 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 In a recent conversation, an official of one company expressed concern about the difficulty faced by its subsidiary in fulfilling a contract. This was due to financing problems, i.e., difficulties in obtaining loans.   \par \par \uc2 Due to legal lending limitations, the subsidiary was denied a loan by a bank despite having a good name, a job contract and a very strong balance sheet. The bank required collateral in the form of the personal assets of the directors -- a request which, of course, was refused.   \par \par \uc2 The company official continued by saying that lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would not be followed by significantly stronger corporate lending, unless loan requirements were eased.   \par \par \uc2 Not long ago, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  unveiled plans to relax the loan requirement regulations, including issuing new rules such as increasing the limit for lending to affiliated parties, lowering the requirements for loan classification, and providing research and database services for the national and local economies.   \par \par \uc2 However, apart from more accommodating regulations, banks also need to be able to forecast business prospects (i.e., profitability and business environment), before loan growth can increase significantly.   \par \par \uc2 This requires predictability as regards macroeconomic variables and other business assumptions. Unfortunately, it is well understood and already the consensus that Indonesia is lacking in these aspects. We would now like to take a closer look the predictability aspect in the assessment of a hypothetical corporate loan.   \par \par \uc2 Consider the palm-oil business, one of the government's priority sectors. It takes seven years for a palm tree to reach its optimum productive age. On undeveloped land, it will take at least eight to nine years.   \par \par \uc2 Let's consider what happened in regard to the regulatory environment. In the space of one month, there was talk of limiting palm-oil exports to ensure sufficient supplies to the biofuel industry, as well as a plan to increase export duty so as to ensure cooking-oil supplies.   \par \par \uc2 This was just one month! It needs to be remembered here that to reach the optimum age for oil palms, it takes two administrations. This example is just one highlighting the flip-flops that often occur in the national spectrum; with decentralization, more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  can arise as we go down to the more parochial levels of government.   \par \par \uc2 By the end of November 2006, bank lending had grown by approximately 10 percent for that year to around Rp 767 trillion, lower than the 23 percent recorded during the same period of 2005. Non-performing loans were stable at 8 percent, while net interest margins were still at a healthy 5.8 percent.   \par \par \uc2 The Loan to Deposit Ratio was at a low 61 percent. Indonesia's Loan-to-GDP ratio is still low at approximately 23 percent, compared to India at 39 percent, Thailand at 75 percent and Malaysia at 107 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Currently, the banking industry is in a very liquid position. Total third party deposits stood at Rp 1,251 trillion as of the end of November 2006, representing growth of 10.9 percent for the first eleven months of last year. In addition, roughly 12 percent of total banking productive assets were invested in \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  bills.   \par \par \uc2 With the nominal amount of deposits throughout the banking system being 60 percent higher than the nominal amount of loans, similar growth rates in deposits and loans would lead to a rise in liquidity.   \par \par \uc2 Before loan growth can rise rapidly, we expect to see the banks focusing on lending to businesses with higher predictability levels, from consumer loans, such as vehicle-financing and mortgages, to medium loans financing trade and services. This is a pattern we've been seeing for several years.   \par \par \uc2 Bank loans for services-based sectors (also known as the tertiary sector in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  jargon) have been growing at a rate of 16 percent per year, while loans for manufacturing-based industries (known as the secondary sector) have been growing at a snail's pace of 5 percent per year.   \par \par \uc2 Financing manufacturing industry is often considered hazardous to a bank's health. The irony is that, second to agriculture, the secondary sector employs more people per unit of investment than the tertiary sector.   \par \par \uc2 But who would lend to an industry that has potentially explosive labor problems? Who would be paid first in the event of bankruptcy: labor or the creditors?   \par \par \uc2 Before lending growth can become broad-based, we need to first start by addressing the source of unpredictability: regulatory and law-enforcement risks.   \par \par \uc2 Shoddy Infrastructure is only one problem; but bigger ones concern the soft aspects. Investors should be able to predict with confidence that there will be minimal changes to a given \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  during their investment horizon. Investors also need to be afforded certainty that the law will be upheld in court should a dispute arise, and that court decisions will be enforced.   \par \par \uc2 Institutionalizing the importance of having coherent and consistent policies, along with a predictable judicial system, will take time to realize. So, for the time being, we can expect to see the services-based industries growing at a faster pace than manufacturing industries.   \par \par \uc2 Reducing unemployment through private sector investment will thus become harder.   \par \par \uc2 Let's just hope higher government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on infrastructure projects can fill the void.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070131e31v00010\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
