\par\par \b \uc2 Who's to blame for slow  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  reform?  \b0\par\par\uc2 Winarno Zain , Jakarta  \par \uc2 1,062 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 February 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 The central government has been criticized for its weak implementation of, and lack of commitment to, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform. It has also been criticized for its slow progress in improving Indonesia's investment climate. But maybe it's time to look closer, and ask if the government really should bear all the blame.  \par \par \uc2 Problems with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform -- and its slow progress -- arise because \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform starts with \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . That is why it is so important to have a \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  that really understands what \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform is all about; why it is necessary to create more jobs for millions of people and to ease the hardship of those who still live in poverty.  \par \par \uc2 Lack of awareness on the part of the House on the importance of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform has slowed the progress of this much-needed agenda. Several bills that deal with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform have been shelved by the House for reasons that are unclear. It is not clear when the House will start deliberating those bills. But the enactment of those bills into law is urgently required if Indonesia is to attract more investment.  \par \par \uc2 The bills include the draft new investment law that would provide legal certainty and equal rights and obligations for foreign as well as domestic investors; the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform bills aimed at simplifying \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  administration, and balancing the relationship between taxpayers and \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  authorities in terms of their obligations and sanctions; bills on mining, which face opposition from mining companies; and the draft bill revising current labor laws, with a view to reducing company labor costs.  \par \par \uc2 However odd it seems, it has to be admitted that the President should not be the only one to blame for the current lackluster progress of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform. After all, the Indonesian Constitution assigns most power of \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 .  \par \par \uc2 According to the Constitution the central government does not have a monopoly on political power. Decision-making powers are dispersed among several state institutions and regional governments. Although the government, as the executive branch, has the central role in implementing reforms, the success of those reforms requires the support and commitment of other institutions. Unfortunately, those institutions have different perceptions on the urgency for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform.  \par \par \uc2 The judiciary has also shared some of the blame for the lack of progress of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform. Some court decisions on corporate disputes have been controversial in the past, and were considered odd by the business community in the face of the growing dynamism of business practices.  \par \par \uc2 One should not forget how Manulife, the giant Canadian insurance company, was declared bankrupt by a court in Jakarta several years ago. Recently, the Indonesian Supreme Court upheld a decision by a lower court that declared invalid US$500 million in notes issued by Indah Kiat Paper & Pulp, a subsidiary of Sinar Mas group.  \par \par \uc2 Indah Kiat argued the notes issued by its offshore special purpose vehicles companies were unlawful, since they violated Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and securities laws, even though Indah Kiat had benefited from the notes and had even been paying interest on them. The losses suffered by investors who bought the notes have sent ripples across the financial community and damaged the investment climate in Indonesia.  \par \par \uc2 The Supreme Court still has a long way to go to improve judges' knowledge of modern business practices. They have yet to transform the court into a judicial institution that commands respect and credibility, that is free from corruption, and that has a high regard for the sanctity of the business contract. Until the Supreme Court reforms itself, it will be difficult for investors to have peace of mind when doing business in this country.  \par \par \uc2 The Constitutional Court, another independent judicial body created by the amended Constitution, has the authority to exercise judicial review on laws, and to annul articles that they deem contradict the Constitution. This has occurred with the New Oil and Gas Law and the Electricity Law.  \par \par \uc2 Therefore, even if a reform bill has been passed by the House to become law, it is not free from challenges to its legality. Decisions by Constitutional Court have the potential to create legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and set back the progress of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform.  \par \par \uc2 Even if the President has no power to legislate a bill into law, he still has the power to influence the outcome of deliberation on that bill in the House. Therefore it is strange that President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono did not intervene aggressively when a certain reform bill got bogged down in the House.  \par \par \uc2 The President, as the chief executive, has a responsibility to ensure that all bills that have strategic importance, such as those dealing with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform, are approved by the House immediately. By shying away from this responsibility, the President can send the wrong signal to the market that he is personally detached and uncommitted to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform.  \par \par \uc2 There are ways in which the President can influence the House. He could lobby the House to immediately pass reform bills into law. To do this, he would need a strong lobbying team, made up of experienced politicians, who still maintain personal contact with House committee members and who are familiar with consensus building and the inner workings of a House committee.  \par \par \uc2 Alternatively, he could ask the political parties that make up his "coalition" Cabinet to exercise pressure on the House. Despite the existence of criticism of the way the President formed his cabinet, it is ironic that, at this point in time, this coalition cabinet could be an asset to the President when it comes to passing certain bills.  \par \par \uc2 In addition, being part of "coalition" government, means that the governing parties have a moral obligation to support any bill submitted by the President to the House for approval. The power of lobbying by the government "coalition" parties has been proved effective when they thwarted several motions by opposition parties in the House to ask clarification on certain government policies.  \par \par \uc2 This was made possible because Vice President Jusuf Kalla, as chairman of the Golkar party personally instructed the Golkar faction in the House to oppose the motions. These same forces could certainly be used by President Yudhoyono, to put pressure on the House to take action on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform bills. If only the President has the will.  \par \par \uc2 The writer is an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  analyst.  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070201e3210000p\par }\page {\p