\par\par \b \uc2 Swiss leader vows to boost RI ties   \b0\par\par\uc2 Veeramalla Anjaiah , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 880 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 February 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Swiss President Micheline Calmy-Rey may be the head of a state with a population smaller than Jakarta, but she has not shied away from a frank discussion of the relationship between her country and Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 The Swiss President, who ended her four-day visit to Indonesia on Saturday, said her country had a good relationship with Indonesia, but both countries could do better to strengthen it.   \par \par \uc2 "The aim (of the visit) was to strengthen our bilateral relationship and enhance bilateral and multilateral cooperation. The trade relationship is at low level and I think we can do better,' President Calmy-Rey, who is also currently the Swiss Foreign Minister, said in an interview with The Jakarta Post and the Kompas newspapers on Friday in Jakarta.   \par \par \uc2 Swiss figures put the volume of bilateral trade between the two countries at US$450 million in 2005, with cumulative Swiss investment in Indonesia reaching around $2.2 billion as of the same year. 75 Swiss companies currently operate in Indonesia, providing 60,000 local jobs.   \par \par \uc2 But compared to Switzerland's total exports and imports, these figures don't add up to much. Switzerland's foreign trade amounts to more than US$300 billion a year. The tiny country is the world's second biggest investor after Japan. At the same time, Indonesia has the biggest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Southeast Asia.   \par \par \uc2 When asked why trade between the two countries wasn't matching this potential, the popular but straightforward Swiss President said she received complaints from some Swiss companies on the difficulties of doing business and investing in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 "I met Swiss businessmen at the embassy. The message is a positive one. But they still asked for better frameworks, legal conditions and more stability," she said.   \par \par \uc2 On the question of investment, Calmy-Rey said a government can't force private investors to invest in a country.   \par \par \uc2 "They (investors) come if they feel the climate is positive and the framework is okay. Otherwise they don't. The biggest Swiss companies in Indonesia say there are still difficulties," Calmy-Rey said.   \par \par \uc2 Calmy-Rey said President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono was interested in knowing more about how Switzerland achieved its international competitiveness. The small but rich state was ranked number one for global competitiveness in 2006 by the World \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Forum, ahead of the U.S. and other world powers.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia ranked 50th on the same list, a big jump from 69th in 2005.   \par \par \uc2 "I spoke with the President about competitiveness and the conditions for competitiveness. The President was very interested in what made Switzerland ranked first. I told him it depended upon several factors -- political institutions, the legal framework, \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  law, education, infrastructure and so on," Calmy-Rey said.   \par \par \uc2 President Yudhoyono told Calmy-Rey he would send a team to Switzerland to study how \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  competitiveness was achieved there.   \par \par \uc2 When asked about corruption in Indonesia, Calmy-Rey said she lacked a deep understanding of the issue.   \par \par \uc2 "I can't speak about it because I don't really know the reality in this country. But I heard several times about the obstacle of corruption. It's a difficulty. I heard this from the Swiss business community. It's really a problem for them," she said.   \par \par \uc2 According to Calmy-Rey, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not a favorable condition for business.   \par \par \uc2 "It (\b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) is a poison for business," she said bluntly.   \par \par \uc2 Calmy-Rey said the political relationship between the two countries needed the same work as the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  one.   \par \par \uc2 "I think at the political level, we could have more regular meetings. I am the first president of Switzerland to come here since (Indonesia's) independence more than 60 years ago," she said.   \par \par \uc2 Switzerland, according to Calmy-Rey, sees Indonesia -- the biggest Muslim country in the world, which has democratic and pluralistic credentials -- as an important nation in Asia. She said both countries have similarities and common positions on global issues.   \par \par \uc2 "(On international issues) we try to play the role of bridge builders and we have a tolerant attitudes toward other languages, cultures and civilizations,' said Calmy-Rey, the architect of Switzerland's new "active neutrality" foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Calmy-Rey said Switzerland had so far focused more on its neighbors and other European countries. But she said this was changing.   \par \par \uc2 "If we look at the world today, it's not the world of 19th century. It (our foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) was no longer adapted to the reality of the world," she said.   \par \par \uc2 "So we decided to reorganize and to think about a strategy more adapted to today's world. That meant increasing our presence in Asia and stabilizing our presence in Europe."   \par \par \uc2 She said Switzerland's active relationship towards Indonesia must be seen in light of this changing \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Calmy-Rey said Switzerland was also interested in knowing more about Muslims in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 "I met with Indonesian representatives from different religions... it is interesting for us because we have half a million Muslims in Switzerland and (such talks) give us a more comprehensive view," Calmy-Rey said.   \par \par \uc2 Before her departure, the Swiss President inaugurated a repaired drinking water plant at Lambaro, Aceh Besar regency in Aceh. The rehabilitation work was done by Switzerland at a cost of four million Swiss francs (Rp 40 billion).   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070212e32c0000z\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
