\par\par \b \uc2 Consolidating RI democracy 'should come organically'  \b0\par\par\uc2 Ridwan Max Sijabat , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta  \par \uc2 477 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 March 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post  \par \par \uc2 Political analysts have suggested that reducing the number of political parties -- a move needed to strengthen the presidential system -- should go through a natural selection process for the sake of democracy and pluralism.  \par \par \uc2 Ray Rangkuti, executive director of the Civil Circle for Indonesia (LIMA), and Indria Samego from the Indonesian Institute of Sciences (LIPI) said in a political discussion organized by the Golkar Party on Thursday that political intervention to raise electoral thresholds in the 2009 general elections would kill democracy and could end in political chaos.  \par \par \uc2 Rangkuti said it would be too abrupt for a higher electoral threshold to be set, despite eight years of political reform, while Indria argued that a strong presidential system was dependent not only on a strong \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but also on the strong leadership of the president.  \par \par \uc2 "Indonesia should stick to current laws and let the reduction of political parties contending the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  and presidential elections unfold in a natural manner," he said.  \par \par \uc2 He predicted that under the current laws, the number of political parties would keep decreasing until it reached an ideal number after several elections.  \par \par \uc2 A 2002 law on political parties allows a party to be registered if it has chapters in at least 50 percent of the provinces, branches in 50 percent of the regencies and in 25 percent of provincial districts.  \par \par \uc2 A 2003 law on \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  elections requires eligible parties to have chapters in at least two thirds of the provinces and branches in two thirds of regencies and mayoralties with at least 1,000 voters.  \par \par \uc2 "Although some 30 political parties have already registered with the Justice and Human Rights Ministry, it is still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  whether they are eligible to contend the 2009 elections," said Rangkuti.  \par \par \uc2 With a 3 percent threshold detailed in the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  elections law, only seven of 16 political parties with seats in the parliament are eligible to contend the 2009 elections.  \par \par \uc2 "So, the number of eligible parties will potentially reduce to maybe 10 in 2009, from 24 in 2004 and 48 in 1999," he said, noting that parties failing to meet the electoral threshold have to merge or join other parties.  \par \par \uc2 This natural selection process would continue during the presidential elections because only parties with at least 15 percent of seats in the House or 20 percent of the total votes in the 2004 presidential elections are allowed to nominate candidates.  \par \par \uc2 Indria said Indonesia needed strong leaders committed to implementing principles of democracy including modernity, pluralism and checks-and-balances.  \par \par \uc2 He said President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, elected directly by the people, should demonstrate his strong leadership to achieve significant progress in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. At the same time, the House should enhance its control function and the judiciary should be tough in law enforcement to avoid a "democratic dictatorship".  \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070302e3320000w\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
