\par\par \b \uc2 Syaikhu Usman: Urging civil society via research   \b0\par\par\uc2 Khairul Saleh , The Jakarta Post, Palembang   \par \uc2 1,000 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 April 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 For Syaikhu Usman, the field of research is nothing new. With about three decades of research projects under his belt, Syaikhu, 62, the founder and a senior researcher at the SMERU Research Institute in Jakarta, has conducted much research related to poverty eradication and decentralization, as well as regional autonomy.   \par \par \uc2 Syaikhu is interested in these areas because their development and influence -- which are highly significant in the growth and life of a community -- are much determined by government policies. He has thus tried his best to ensure that the resulting reports will receive attention from appropriate government officials.   \par \par \uc2 "Besides, these reports must also reach various social groups in order to stimulate them to play their role in discussions that concern the interests of the many," said Syaikhu when The Jakarta Post visited his office recently in Menteng, Jakarta.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  life, as described in Article 33 of the 1945 Constitution, essentially places community welfare above individual prosperity.   \par \par \uc2 This concept parallels the ideas of sustainable development aimed at developing the \b \highlight22\uc2 public economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , at the same time serving as a guideline to enable social transformation. In this, one goal must not be deemed more important than the other; the two must instead be integrated.   \par \par \uc2 "In this context, the main constraint is that the people, particularly the poor, often do not have any space where they can demonstrate their capability and independence," Syaikhu said.   \par \par \uc2 Under the New Order regime, this constraint assumed a greater magnitude because that administration was centralized and autocratic. These aspects reinforced each other and tended to ignore the people's aspiration, including the aspirations of regional administrations.   \par \par \uc2 During this administration, various policies on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth were drawn up by the central government and implemented by its agencies. Meanwhile, positions in the regions deemed strategic, either politically or economically, went to those appointed directly by the central government. On the grounds of maintaining national stability and cohesion, civilian positions were even accorded to the military.   \par \par \uc2 This trend was reversed when the New Order government ended as a result of mounting \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  pressure calling for democracy in every sector of the nation and the state. This pressure, along with other variables, has eventually brought about direct general elections and a free press, and in general encouraged the revival of civil society.   \par \par \uc2 A similar trend began to emerge in regional autonomy policies, with their execution becoming directed toward decentralization and democratization.   \par \par \uc2 But this change has also led to social \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , restlessness, suspicion and tension.   \par \par \uc2 "Even so, but for this change there would never be any improvement," said Syaikhu. "Therefore, we must see in every change a process that is no less important than the outcome. The purpose is to ensure the development of a dignified democracy."   \par \par \uc2 The implementation of sustainable development requires a democratic process. This means that the government must allow the broadest opportunity for community participation. Regional autonomy is an effort to bring the people, business players and regional apparatuses closer within the process of development.   \par \par \uc2 Awareness of respecting people's culture and capability is crucial, as the central government's capacity is basically limited under a decentralized system.   \par \par \uc2 Syaikhu is optimistic that if local government apparatuses -- for example at the village level -- are provided with the education, awareness and leeway to net the people's aspirations and to understand their socio-political environment, much can be accomplished on the basis of the capability and wisdom of the people. If people are actively involved in innovating and creating, the government's burden in accelerating and guiding the betterment of people's welfare will be lighter.   \par \par \uc2 "To arrive at this condition, three major factors must be revamped: the attitude of the bureaucracy must be neutralized; the function of political parties must be put on course and people's organizations must be strengthened," said Syaikhu.   \par \par \uc2 The senior researcher embarked upon his career in 1976, when he joined the Social Sciences Training program in Banda Aceh, Nanggroe Aceh Darussalam, in which he was named "best participant". Since then, Syaikhu, a humble man who maintains a low profile, has received many opportunities to improve the quality of his research and his identity in the field.   \par \par \uc2 The grounded research method -- which he learned during the training program -- became an asset in his advancing along his chosen career path.   \par \par \uc2 According to Syaikhu, this method makes him freer and more comfortable in expressing his results in research reports, because they are based on the findings and events found in a particular community.   \par \par \uc2 "Knowledge that has its origins in another place is an auxiliary instrument in understanding the social dynamism in the community that forms the subject of research. A research program can disclose and reveal what and how the people's condition really stands," said Syaikhu.   \par \par \uc2 Indeed, his writings often explore the practical problems that affect people's daily lives, and his research reports often relate to \b \highlight22\uc2 public policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This is understandable, given that the two main research institutes where Syaikhu has worked specialize in \b \highlight22\uc2 public policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 : the Center for \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Implementation Studies (1985-1997) and the SMERU Research Institute (1998-present).   \par \par \uc2 Among the research he has conducted are: the life of Chinese peasants in a suburb of Palembang, South Sumatra (1978), the typology of government aid performance in rural areas (1988), the impact of the Presidential Instruction on underdeveloped rural areas (1995), agricultural strategies (1997), the business climate under regional autonomy (2001), local policies and decentralization (2003), microfinance for the poor (2005) and cash aid program (2006).   \par \par \uc2 Syaikhu was born in 1945 in Tanjung Batu village, Ogan Ilir, South Sumatra. He and his siblings all attended a local pesantren , or Islamic boarding school, but Syaikhu alone broke away from his family's educational tradition.   \par \par \uc2 He pursued further studies in Yogyakarta, where he obtained his Bachelors at the Teachers Training Institute (IKIP), then ventured still further -- educationally and geographically -- earning his Masters and doctorate at the Department of Development Sociology, Cornell University.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070412e34c0001k\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
