\par\par \b \uc2 A rock and a hard place   \b0\par\par\uc2 David E. Sumual , Jakarta   \par \uc2 730 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 April 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The issue of a Cabinet reshuffle has come into the spotlight again after Vice President Jusuf Kalla spoke at an extraordinary consultation meeting in Yogyakarta last Friday. In fact, Golkar has been demanding a reshuffle since the end of last year.   \par \par \uc2 Golkar's deputy general chairman and speaker of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Agung Laksono, put forward the names of 15 party members to fill 10 Cabinet positions. Golkar feels its stance is reasonable. After all, it holds more seats in the House than any other party (23 percent) and yet still only has three cabinet posts.   \par \par \uc2 Golkar's demands have intensified after survey results revealed the popularity of the President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono and Golkar to be on the wane. Indeed, Megawati Soekarnoputri's Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDIP) has become more popular than Golkar, after rises in food prices -- particularly rice -- pushed many people into greater \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  hardship. Golkar also believes a Cabinet reshuffle is necessary given the poor health of some current ministers.   \par \par \uc2 The issue of a reshuffle is a hot topic in Indonesia. During Golkar's National Leadership Meeting last October, 22 of the 33 provincial branches proposed Golkar withdraw its support for the government. Such calls came after the president established the Presidential Working Unit for the Management of Programs and Reform (UKP3R), apparently without consulting Kalla.   \par \par \uc2 Now it appears that Golkar is once again seeking a Cabinet reshuffle. This time, however, it seems to be trying to use the government's controversial support of the UN Security Council's resolution on Iran as its trump card. Some Golkar members have called on the president to reshuffle the Cabinet by April 21 at the latest, to put pressure on the president before the issue is settled during a plenary session on May 6.   \par \par \uc2 Over the last two weeks, President Yudhoyono has given mixed signals about any Cabinet reshuffle. On April 15 he dismissed calls for a reshuffle, saying it would only disrupt the government's work. In this regard, it appears Yudhoyono is too calculating in his efforts to hold on to power. He does not realize that, from the people's perspective, his excessively cautious style is a disappointment, coming as it does after his promises of more resolution and decisiveness.   \par \par \uc2 Yudhoyono is now between a rock and a hard place. On the one hand, he may want to maintain his present Cabinet, choosing the path of least resistance and letting problems be solved by his current ministers. With this option, the current modest \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth may continue up to at least 2009.   \par \par \uc2 On the other hand, Yudhoyono could reshuffle the Cabinet soon. Although Golkar might attain more power, the move would at least give the impression the government is looking out for the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest. This move -- in addition to bureaucratic reform -- would hopefully raise hopes among the people for a better life.   \par \par \uc2 Indeed, a Cabinet reshuffle is one of those quick-fix solutions that could improve the government's image, although not necessarily its performance. The Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Boediono has so far succeeded in creating macroeconomic stability. However, the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's confidence of the government's ability to revive the real sector has been diminishing as both poverty and the unemployment rate have continued to increase.   \par \par \uc2 The general view of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  is that the government is now struggling to solve the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems. After two and a half years in power, the administration is still slow to amend key laws, such as those on \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and labor, thereby discouraging investment in labor-intensive sectors.   \par \par \uc2 The government is also aiming to increase annual infrastructure investment to 6-7 percent of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in five years, with the goal of accelerating the annual GDP growth rate to 7 percent on a sustainable basis. Yet skepticism now abounds. This is because many projects have failed to get off the ground and have remained no more than talk.   \par \par \uc2 Both Yudhoyono and Kalla are contributing to the prolonged \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over a Cabinet reshuffle by sending conflicting signals. The risk, of course, is that those ministers currently in the Cabinet will delay making important \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  decisions, as they wait for any reshuffle announcement.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is an analyst from the Danareksa Research Institute. This is his personal view.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070420e34k0000i\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
