\par\par \b \uc2 Standard Chartered aims big despite market  \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 The Jakarta Post , Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,022 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 May 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The banking sector is often blamed for failing to serve as an intermediary for the real sector, due to its perceived preference for parking its money in \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  promissory notes rather than giving loans.   \par \par \uc2 In response, banks say the risk of giving loans to companies remains high partly because of factors such as business \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , too much bureaucracy and weak labor competitiveness.   \par \par \uc2 Against this background, Standard Chartered saw lending percentage growth of 27 percent in 2006, almost twice the industry average of 14 percent.   \par \par \uc2 StanChart regional CEO for South East and South Asia Jaspal Singh Bindra was in Indonesia earlier this month and sat down with The Jakarta Post 's Andi Haswidi to talk about the bank's plans for its operations in Indonesia and how it has coped with the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the market here. The following are excerpts of the interview.   \par \par \uc2 Where do you see Indonesia in the regional market, in terms of its potential?   \par \par \uc2 We think Southeast Asia is very vibrant as an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . A large part of Southeast Asia was hugely dependent on the U.S. performance, now we have a double sustaining power, which is China, for some more neighboring countries even India, but to a larger extent China.   \par \par \uc2 So that is a kind of double-barrel situation now. In terms of growth potential because of trade, etc., and Southeast Asia is roughly about one fifth of the contribution to the entire bank, that is quite significant.   \par \par \uc2 If you look at the region and broke it up by country, they are all likely to grow quite significantly. Particularly Indonesia. We think we have taken a very long-term view of Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 We think Indonesia, given its large population, given its rich resources, can only go one way. That is obviously the challenge of leadership and management. The country has had some \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  challenges, not no mention the natural calamities, more than its share, but now, by withstanding, it shows great progress.   \par \par \uc2 So, what's in store for this year's expansion plan?   \par \par \uc2 We are going to focus a lot more on organic growth, because the opportunity of growing organically in most of our footprint is much more attractive.   \par \par \uc2 As Asia, the Middle East, Africa, become very attractive, acquisition, first of all, has become difficult, and second it has become very expensive. On the other hand, the opportunity to grow organically has become much more attractive.   \par \par \uc2 Is there any specific target for Indonesian market growth?   \par \par \uc2 Broadly, the message is that in terms of capital investment, resource investment and product initiation, Indonesia is right up there at the top; it is one of our top potential markets.   \par \par \uc2 We even put our money into another bank (Bank Permata). So, we do believe that this is a future market for us.   \par \par \uc2 I think the tailored target we have is that we should in every three to four years double from where we are. That is our internal aspiration.   \par \par \uc2 Has there been progress by the government in terms of regulations that can help business growth?   \par \par \uc2 Yes, we have seen that quite clearly. I think in areas such as Islamic banking, where the government is now looking, opening up \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is great. I think in terms of the project financing area, in terms of the mining sites, we see a lot of support from the government promoting entrepreneurial investment, the results of which would have to be good for the banks.   \par \par \uc2 So we are quite in favor of the government opening up for the industry players. I think so far we had a pretty good run with the regulators, in terms of we had a choice of branches that we wanted to open, we had the choice of doing business that we wanted to do.   \par \par \uc2 What are the most pressing challenges hampering growth here?   \par \par \uc2 I think there are two. One is talent. Talent is probably the biggest gap. It is in most of the emerging markets. But I'd say a little bit more acute in Indonesia than in other competing growing markets.   \par \par \uc2 The second is the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over growth. And it's not that we are disturbed by it's not happening as quickly, it's just the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 You know there is a view that the 2009 elections, there will be a boom, and typically there is in most pre-election years, there is a huge boom, but it is still very difficult to see it yet. So if it should happen, it should happen next year or later this year. But we don't see it, so how do we program for that. And will that last through the election or will it be short-lived.   \par \par \uc2 It's that kind of stuff whereas in some other markets it's quite clear. I think in time Indonesia will overcome such \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Recently, the government has been pressing the banks to further cut \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in order to boost lending. Your comment?   \par \par \uc2 If you look at Standard Chartered, clearly from what I have seen is that just in 2006, our loans increased by over 27 percent, whereas the industry average was 14 percent. We are clearly almost two times that of the average of the industry.   \par \par \uc2 So I don't think we are shying away from increasing our exposure to industry or the local market, in spite of the concerns.   \par \par \uc2 I think we are doing more than our fair share if we are doing almost two times compared to what the local banks are doing. We have some points on that one. We are in the business of taking risks, as long as you can manage those risks. So I think it's not a question of shying away from a risky situation; if so you shouldn't be in the market in the first place.   \par \par \uc2 It's the management of the risk that we feel more confident and comfortable with. We don't want to comment on our competitors, but all we are saying is that the statistics show that they are a little bit shier than we are.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070528e35s00010\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
