\par\par \b \uc2 Is Australia's Howard era really coming to an end?   \b0\par\par\uc2 Hilman Adil ,  Jakarta   \par \uc2 825 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 June 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 What should we make of recent \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion polls that appear to show Australian opposition Labor Party leader Kevin Rudd eclipsing John Howard as preferred prime minister?   \par \par \uc2 In January, political pollster Newspoll had Labor's preferred vote at 56 percent compared to the current government's 45 percent. Providing no major changes in the political climate occur, either domestically or internationally, voter loyalties are unlikely to change come the federal election at the end of this year. However, we should also keep in mind the words of well-known author Gore Vidal, who once wrote: "The trouble with Australian politics is that you only see the tip of the ice cube."   \par \par \uc2 The Howard era began in 1996 and spanned a decade full of regional and global challenges including the Asian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis of 1997, the fall of Soeharto in 1998, an Australian-led intervention in East Timor in 1999, the Sept. 11, 2001, attack on the World Trade Center, the wars in Afghanistan and Iraq and the 2002 and 2005 Bali and 2004 Jakarta bombings.   \par \par \uc2 After 11 years in office and with a strong \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and popular new \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  behind him, how does one account for Howard's diminishing appeal to the Australian \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? Basically, Australians have grown tired of the Howard government. In a way, his success has been his downfall. The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is growing so strongly that many Australians seem willing to take a risk by voting for a new government, especially considering that a Labor government under Kevin Rudd does not seem to threaten their interests.   \par \par \uc2 The Iraq war will be an important factor in how 71 percent of people vote. A poll last February found that 62 percent of Australians opposed Howard's handling of the war.   \par \par \uc2 Now, the incumbent prime minister is growing increasingly desperate. One indication of this was his attack on U.S. Senator Barack Obama and the Democratic Party, which was seen by Democrats and some Republicans as a breach of conventional diplomatic behavior. With his well-developed sense of self-preservation, Howard smells a shift in the political climate. He knows that anti-war sentiment is mounting and that the catastrophe in Iraq, for which many feel he is significantly responsible, is becoming a major factor in Australian politics -- particularly since last November's U.S. congressional elections, which saw Republicans lose control of both houses.   \par \par \uc2 Howard now faces an end-of-year election with recent opinion polls indicating that the coalition would not only be defeated but decimated if the vote were to be held today.   \par \par \uc2 Another factor that could impact on the Australian electorate's voting pattern is the nation's shifting demographic dimension, which until now has favored the Liberal-National coalition government, but is now expected to swing in favor of the Labor Party.   \par \par \uc2 Since the mid 1990s, large proportions of older voters (those aged 60 and over) have consistently supported the coalition, with a first preference vote for Howard's government averaging well over 50 percent. Now it seems an overall trend has emerged that is a reversal of the previous trend that saw older voters support the coalition government. This has thus caused a breakdown in the voting pattern.   \par \par \uc2 As the population ages and the movement of "baby boomers" into the ranks of older Australians continues -- thus moderating their conservatism and perhaps reversing it -- it is likely that this voting pattern will also continue. In the course of the last two elections, voters aged in their 50s have turned away from the Howard government. This age group now consists of those born in the late 1940s and early 1950s. The political views of these "late bloomers", who came of age in the Whitlam era, were probably influenced at a time when social reforms flourished and a rejection of hyper-individualism was generally the mood of the younger generation.   \par \par \uc2 The Australian electorate has traditionally rated Labor above the Liberals on social issues such as health and education, but below, and potentially dangerously so, on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and national security issues. Over time, however, Rudd has been able to neutralize Howard's grip on national security and the latter's efforts to portray the former as being \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  and ambiguous on the war in Iraq do not seem to have worked.   \par \par \uc2 On \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues, it is to Howard's benefit that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is performing well, unemployment has fallen and world conditions are favorable. Labor seems to be performing better, however, in promoting itself as an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  manager. Rudd's cautious and conservative image have put to rest fears that Labor is incapable of managing the Australian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Though Howard's ability to survive has surprised and perhaps impressed many in the past, hordes of observers are now insisting that this last hill will prove too high.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is Emeritus Research Professor at the Indonesian Institute of Sciences (LIPI).   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070605e3650000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichg