\par\par \b \uc2 Bush pulls climate change trick, offers nothing   \b0\par\par\uc2 Stevie Emilia , Jakarta   \par \uc2 956 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 June 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Like a magician, U.S. President George W. Bush has cast his climate change spell, stunning his audience with some sleight of hand.   \par \par \uc2 Standing on center stage, under the spotlight of allegations that his country was foot-dragging in tackling climate change and was trying to water down a climate treaty, he cast a spell just days ahead of the Group of Eight (G8) summit in Germany on June 6-8, where global warming is expected to be a major topic.   \par \par \uc2 His proposal was a long-term deal on cuts among 15 big emitters led by the U.S., China, Russia and India. The statement Thursday, which could mark a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  shift that would allow U.S. greenhouse gas emissions to increase through 2012, included a plan to hold a series of meetings to set long-term goals by the end of 2008, just a month before Bush ends his final term in January 2009.   \par \par \uc2 The downside of Bush's proposal is that each country would voluntarily set their own goals -- on how they want to cut greenhouse gases in the next 10 to 20 years, lower air pollution and improve energy security. The leading emitter, intentionally or not, omitted any sort of details that might have helped it shed its climate change doubter image.   \par \par \uc2 For one, there is no binding agreement to limit emissions, including a commitment by the U.S. There also are no timetables, or whether the big emitters in the new pact will take into account existing international efforts to deal with the problem, such as the one spearheaded by the UN that is currently working to find a successor to the Kyoto Protocol, the only climate change treaty which limits greenhouse gas emissions but will expire in 2012.   \par \par \uc2 The idea of finding a successor to the protocol, which commits developed countries to cut emissions by 5 percent from 1990 levels by 2008-2012, but exempts developing countries from the obligation, is underway and will be put before a larger meeting of the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change in December this year in Bali, where UN officials hope to launch formal talks on a post-Kyoto treaty.   \par \par \uc2 It is hard to imagine the U.S. might shift its classic climate change stance just days before the G8 meeting, although the White House did say the new proposal complements ongoing multinational efforts to tackle global warming and might result in a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  shift, but did not explain how and which \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 It is still fresh in mind that the U.S. chief climate negotiator, Harlan Watson ,was reported as saying by Reuters during a UN-hosted climate change meeting in Bonn in May this year that for the sake of not jeopardizing its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, his country will continue funding clean energy technologies to fight climate change, while rejecting emissions targets or caps and trade schemes.   \par \par \uc2 Bush's latest statement did not do much to polish his image as critics judged the statement a mere diversion, accusing Bush of trying to set unenforceable targets for curbing greenhouse gasses, with no real limits on emissions and no carbon trading. Some accused him of trying to avoid taking action until he leaves office.   \par \par \uc2 With the statement, Bush also raised questions about whether the new proposal he has in mind will be similar to the existing Asia-Pacific Partnership voluntary program, where the U.S. is working with Australia, China, India, Japan and South Korea to attract private money for cleaner energy technologies.   \par \par \uc2 Historically, the questions make sense considering that the U.S. did sign a global agreement on climate talks in 1992 but then refused to ratify the Kyoto Protocol, with Bush arguing the protocol would be \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  suicide since it leaves out fast-growing economies like China and India.   \par \par \uc2 With his latest statement, Bush has refrained from taking the bold step. He failed to live up to the expectation that as the world's largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the leading emitter of greenhouse gasses, the U.S. might take a leadership role in tackling climate change.   \par \par \uc2 He also failed to respond to the severity of the crisis that most of the rest of the world, including many U.S. residents and politicians themselves, has long since recognized.   \par \par \uc2 Bush should not take any consolation in his proposal being welcomed by European leaders, including the host of the G8 meeting German Chancellor Angela Merkel, who found the proposal provides a "common ground".   \par \par \uc2 Unlike Bush, Merkel herself has thrown her support behind an ambitious plan to restrict the average global temperature rise to 3.6 degrees, which would require a global reduction in emissions of 50 percent below 1990 levels by 2050.   \par \par \uc2 Bush should be able see what is coming.   \par \par \uc2 Numerous studies involving experts from diverse backgrounds have delivered their verdicts: the planet we call home is definitely getting warmer.   \par \par \uc2 This year, UN reports have projected more desertification, floods, heat waves and rising sea levels because of rising temperatures due to greenhouse gas emissions, mostly from fossil fuels. Of the 12 warmest years on record, 11 took place between 1995 and 2006.   \par \par \uc2 Back in the U.S., many states, such as California, are pushing for tough limits on greenhouse gas emissions while some big companies have joined the move.   \par \par \uc2 Bush should realize it is no longer time to do everything in his own way and on his own terms.   \par \par \uc2 With time no longer on our side, it is time to put away old \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and stop playing tricks. After trashing the planet for generations, it is the moment to work together, not alone, to fix the problem.   \par \par \uc2 The author is a staff writer at The Jakarta Post.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070607e3670000q\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
