\par\par \b \uc2 On responsible business   \b0\par\par\uc2 753 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 July 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Even though the concept of corporate social responsibility (CSR) is most apropos in Indonesia, where commercial law is inadequate, law enforcement weak and the bureaucracy perceived as being corrupt, making CSR legally mandatory, as the new corporations' bill intends to do, is an ill-timed move that could create even more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  for investors.   \par \par \uc2 We therefore support the stance of the 20 industrial associations that have demanded that the provision making CSR compulsory for companies in Indonesia be dropped from the bill on limited liability corporations, which is currently in the early phase of deliberation in the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The associations are not against the concept of CSR per se, but simply say that making it compulsory would impose a further onerous burden on companies at a time when most of them are still struggling to get to grips with a vast array of other laws and regulations.   \par \par \uc2 Indeed, simply complying with the numerous enactments on environmental, social and governance issues is already an uphill struggle for most domestic companies. Moreover, the CSR concept varies from one country to another, and comes in many shapes and forms. Many see it as socially responsible, ethically right and environmentally friendly investment, but others consider the concept to simply be part of good corporate governance.   \par \par \uc2 But the essence of the concept, as the United Nations Global Compact business leaders' summit in Geneva early this month reaffirmed, is that it is no longer sufficient for companies to merely comply with the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  if they are really serious about sustainable development and contributing to poverty alleviation.   \par \par \uc2 The problem, though, is that there are as yet no clear-cut rules, procedures or standards for auditing the implementation of CSR in actual business practice. Hence, making this concept legally binding could create more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  for businesses as investors may find themselves vulnerable to discretionary interpretations and enforcement by officials.   \par \par \uc2 The UN Global Compact itself, which was set up in 2000 and now has around 4,000 corporate members from more than 100 countries, is the world's largest corporate citizenship initiative in promoting the implementation of 10 basic values in the areas of human and labor rights, environment and corruption eradication. All of these principles also, by and large, reflect the CSR concept.   \par \par \uc2 But this UN network is also fully aware of the traps and pitfalls of hastily making the 10 principles compulsory among its members. Instead, it prefers to work on a voluntary basis, relying more on \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  accountability, transparency and the scrutiny of civil society organizations for the promotion of the basic values.   \par \par \uc2 True, the globalization process has redefined the role of business in society as the interdependence between markets, communities and people has deepened and widened the environmental, social and governance issues that business organizations have to cope with.   \par \par \uc2 That is why CSR has increasingly gained recognition among governments, businesses, civil society organizations and international bodies, such as the United Nations, as a most effective means of attacking poverty and reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  inequality.   \par \par \uc2 Companies that uphold CSR principles are especially effective at meeting social needs as these businesses do many things not only to generate profits and abide by the law, but also based on their consciences as good corporate citizens.   \par \par \uc2 The market has begun rewarding companies that adhere to high standards of CSR. Manufacturers of pulp, paper and wooden goods, for example, obtain premium prices for products that are certified as having been produced in line with sustainable development principles. Consumer organizations overseas have often lobbied or even pressured companies not to buy from pulp producers that are well-known for poor environmental management.   \par \par \uc2 An increasing number of investors are incorporating the proper management of environmental, social and governance issues by companies into their investment decisions and value assessments.   \par \par \uc2 Local resentment, and even violence, against a number of resource-based companies in various provinces over the past few years shows how vital the support of local people and communities is for commercial operations.   \par \par \uc2 However, despite the ideals and benefits, overall conditions are not yet appropriate and the legal framework not yet adequate for making CSR mandatory or for imposing CSR values on companies in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 However important CSR principles are for the development of good corporate governance in the widest sense of the term, the government should not let the single article on CSR sabotage the enactment of the new corporations' law as the current \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which was enacted in 1995, has already been rendered obsolete by the rapidly changing business environment.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070717e37h0000j\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
