\par\par \b \uc2 Indonesian law education in the eyes of the victims   \b0\par\par\uc2 M. Ajisatria Suleiman , Jakarta   \par \uc2 738 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 July 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 It was interesting to follow the polemic between Prof. Noortmann ( The Jakarta Post , July 7, 2007) and Prof. Hikmahanto Juwana ( The Jakarta Post , July 12, 2007). However, speaking about reforms to law education in Indonesia is not suffice if the "victims" of this debate -- law students -- have yet to speak.   \par \par \uc2 One lesson learned from Indonesia's inability to recover quickly from the 1997 crisis is the ineffective rule of law, which gave rise to endemic corruption and low quality regulations, to name a few. Justice is the key to Indonesia's development, and this must start from a very basic source: Law education.   \par \par \uc2 I agree with Prof. Hikmahanto that reform is now in progress. Things are not as disastrous as Prof. Noortmann may think.   \par \par \uc2 Law students need to be heard. Students are the "consumers" of the education business. If the quality of law education fails to live up to standards, then students are the direct victims.   \par \par \uc2 First, students need access to legal materials, which range from the constitution to ministerial circulars and court verdicts, whether or not they are recognized as jurisprudence. It is ironic that some students have not even read the country's laws and regulations, only because the materials are not available.   \par \par \uc2 It is difficult to access regulations below presidential decrees, as students need to go directly to the related institutions to obtain them. Moreover, in order to have access to court decisions, students must face the complicated court bureaucracy. It is "standard procedure" to pay money to court officials to expedite the process. For the students, the practice provides them with a crash course and first-hand experience of how judicial corruption works.   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, compilations of court decisions are limited, except in the field of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  law, such as those on intellectual property rights and bankruptcy. Few seem to understand the significance of court decisions, which can help students learn how the law is enforced. Indonesia has a lot of progressive \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but students rarely have the opportunity to study the judicial interpretation of such laws.   \par \par \uc2 Second, students need good teachers, who should not only talk about "text book laws," but also "practical laws". This stresses the significance of court decisions. Even if such court decisions are available, lecturers are unable to present them in the classroom. As a result, students never regard them as an essential source of knowledge.   \par \par \uc2 Speaking of good teachers, I disagree with Prof. Noorthman when implying the side jobs teachers take, such as consultancy projects for foreign donors or NGOs, are counterproductive. Considering a teacher's extremely low salary, moonlighting is unavoidable.   \par \par \uc2 In regard to difficulties in changing the mind-set of teachers, as mentioned by Prof. Hikmahanto, what young lecturers really need is a decent income and clear career planning.   \par \par \uc2 The change in status of four state universities into corporate entities in 2001 left some unfinished homework; lecturers' income and career \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Building new infrastructure without improving the welfare of teachers will result in unsustainable progress.   \par \par \uc2 Finally, and most importantly, students need to be taught integrity. The corrupt Indonesian legal system begins in the law education institutions. Modifying the statement of Prof. Noortmann, I could say that today's corrupt judges and corrupt prosecutors are yesterday's law students. Efforts to combat corruption must begin in law schools.   \par \par \uc2 Law schools must strictly enforce heavy sanctions for plagiarism, fraud and cheating on exams. Law schools should lead by example and have the courage to expel students who are found guilty of such misconducts.   \par \par \uc2 I agree with Prof. Noortmann that foreign donors should stop pouring money into "watch dog" NGOs and training programs. Instead, development funds should be directed to law schools in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 The first step is to improve the accessibility of legal materials by compiling updated regulations and court decisions and making them available in an affordable book format or disseminate the information via the Internet.   \par \par \uc2 The second step is to ensure the welfare of lecturers and create an innovative system to encourage them to spend more time teaching and conducting research.   \par \par \uc2 Last, but certainly not least, strict measures of accountability should be enforced to prevent the misappropriation of funds -- which still occurs in the very place our country's hopes lie for judiciary reform.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is the president of the Student Executive Body (BEM) in the School of Law, at University of Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070720e37k0000u\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
