\par\par \b \uc2 Did the IMF get the crisis right?   \b0\par\par\uc2 Binny Buchori , Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,212 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 July 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 What do we remember about the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis of 10 years ago? Some of my recollections are: Fluctuation of the rupiah's value against the U.S dollar, increasing prices of almost all goods, people rushing to grocery stores, fighting to buy food and household goods that were difficult to find, bank closures causing panic beyond measure all over the country, followed by private enterprises closing due to bankruptcy, causing a dramatic rise in unemployment.   \par \par \uc2 Probably to most Indonesians at that time, the feeling was that of shock and great \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . How would one know that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which for so many years looked robust and gave the impression of stability, would suddenly become so volatile?   \par \par \uc2 Analysts have produced many reports and studies as to why Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  hit rock bottom during the crisis. Some of the issues often discussed as the cause of the crisis are corruption, bad governance and weak \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis did hit Indonesia very badly. One illustration is the soaring external debt. The country struggled to pay its external debt, which increased dramatically from $129 billion in 1996 to $151.2 in 1998. Consequently, the ratio of external debt to GDP also increased from 58.3 percent in 1996 to 167.9 percent in 1998. With this huge debt stock and debt burden, Indonesia sacrificed its resources for servicing the debt.   \par \par \uc2 It is therefore not surprising that Indonesia's crisis has been described as very costly.   \par \par \uc2 To overcome the crisis, the Indonesian government, among heated debate and arguments, asked the International Monetary Fund to come to Indonesia, with the belief that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would recover. The IMF came with a $43 billion bailout as a standby loan.   \par \par \uc2 The heated debate was not baseless, because many Latin American countries and African countries experienced IMF programs in the 1980s and 1990s, when they suffered from financial crises, and there was evidences that IMF programs for tackling \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crises in these countries were not always successful.   \par \par \uc2 There are at least three myths about IMF programs:   \par \par \uc2 First, that they bring new private investors to the countries.   \par \par \uc2 Second, that they increase investor confidence.   \par \par \uc2 Third, they stabilize exchange rates.   \par \par \uc2 The IMF program comes with conditions, known as the Structural Adjustment Program, aimed at generating savings and foreign exchange to fix the balance of payment and facilitate debt repayment. The principle of this is financial stabilization by imposing strict \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary discipline. This approach makes fundamental changes in the way the state functions.   \par \par \uc2 The IMF requires the government to be more efficient, so that it has to cut \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  for fertilizer, oil, education and health. The government also has to allow the market to have a bigger role in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  through the privatization of state-owned enterprises, including water, telecommunications and power firms.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia also had to allow the country to integrate further with the global market by reducing import tariffs and opening up the domestic market to imported goods and international retailers. The government was also obliged to allow the free flow of capital.   \par \par \uc2 Once a country decides to seek a bailout from the IMF, it has to deal with sectoral adjustments, which are facilitated through lending from multilateral and bilateral creditors. In Indonesia, for example, the World Bank, released a huge loan called the \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Reform Support Loan I, amounting to $1 billion.   \par \par \uc2 The ADB gave Indonesia a Financial Guarantee Reform, amounting to $1.5 billion, to develop all necessary regulations and policies for privatization and deregulation in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 Did the prescription work? As experienced in Latin America and African countries, the Structural Adjustment Program created a number of problems. Financial liberalization in Ecuador, combined with the absence of good governance, led to financial crisis and made the government use more than $7 billion of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  funds to bail out banks. ( Structural Adjustment: the SAPRI Report: the \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Roots of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Crisis, Poverty and Inequality , Zed Books, 2004).   \par \par \uc2 In Indonesia, the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , during the IMF program and in the post-IMF period, experienced an increasing cost of living and witnessed a flood of imported goods, from agricultural products to second-hand clothing, as well as international retail businesses.   \par \par \uc2 The flow of agricultural products came as a consequence of the lifting of import tariffs, which at the same time made Indonesia become a net importer of food. In 2003, Indonesia experienced a trade \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of $1.4 billion in food crops and $134.4 million in livestock (Witoro: Memperdagangkan Kehidupan, Menelisik Nasib Beras di bawah Pasal-Pasal WTO in Globalisasi Menghempas Indonesia , LP3ES and Perkumpulan PraKarsa, 2006).   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the prescription of financial stabilization actually created financial destabilization, as shown in the case of the closure of 16 banks with no proper preparation, which resulted in capital outflow amounting to $5 billion.   \par \par \uc2 On this issue, the Independent Evaluation Office (IEO) of the IMF admitted it made a mistake. In the report, The IMF and Recent Capital Account Crisis, Indonesia, Korea and Brazil, 2003 , it stated that the IMF misjudged the severity and the macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  risks in the banking sector.   \par \par \uc2 The intervention lacked a comprehensive bank restructuring strategy and thus the closures deepened the crisis. The report also admitted the IMF failed to understand the different situations in Brazil, Indonesia and South Korea, and yet applied the same remedy.   \par \par \uc2 In Brazil, the IMF identified correctly the problem: macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  imbalance, because that is the expertise of IMF. But in Korea and Indonesia the crisis was caused by weak financial corporate sectors, and the IMF failed to produce an accurate assessment.   \par \par \uc2 The IMF and World Bank gave the same prescription that they gave to Latin America and African countries even though the circumstances were very different. And the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  experience in these countries suggests that the remedy does not always work.   \par \par \uc2 The admission of the IEO reaffirms that they made a the mistake. But the irony is that despite the mistake, Indonesia cannot hold the IMF accountable. Indonesia paid its debt to the IMF in full, no reductions, and there were no sanctions for the institution.   \par \par \uc2 This reaffirms the opinion that it is time that we reformed the governance of the IMF, so that it is transparent and accountable. One of the recommendations from the High-Level Panel on IMF Board Accountability, comprised of scholars, former IMF staff and activists, released in April 2007 by the New Rules of Global Finance, a non-profit organization based in Washington DC, is that IMF should have an external complaint mechanism in the form of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sessions, which would allow the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  to review some of the controversies such as the Asian financial crisis. This would lay down the foundation for the IMF's accountability and would help avoid the same mistakes from being made.   \par \par \uc2 It can be said that the "one size fit all" approach of the International Monetary Fund in tackling the crisis did not work.   \par \par \uc2 The Indonesian crisis should teach all of us that deregulation, privatization and liberalization may not be the one and only solution for crises. To avoid the same mistake in the future there should be a reform in the governance of international financial institutions.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is executive director of Perkumpulan PraKarsa.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070723e37n0000n\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
