\par\par \b \uc2 Subprime jitters shake local market   \b0\par\par\uc2 Urip Hudiono , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 451 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 August 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 A whirlwind of concerns over subprime loans in the U.S. mortgage market continued to undermine investor confidence across markets worldwide Monday, with Indonesian shares and the rupiah being no exception.   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Stock Exchange Composite Index tumbled 80.68 points or 3.6 percent to 2,189.11 on Monday, as last week's plunge on Wall Street triggered investors to sell off holdings in emerging markets.   \par \par \uc2 The rupiah, dragged down by the fall in local stocks, had meanwhile closed at Rp 9,295 to the U.S. dollar, managing to rebound only slightly after slipping to as low as Rp 9,350 on midday trading. The rupiah closed last Friday at Rp 9,270.   \par \par \uc2 The government has kept its calm in spite of the continued jitters of local financial markets.   \par \par \uc2 "We will always monitor every global situation, because even though (the situation) may purely be from external factors, it may likely cause adverse effects to our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  if our fundamentals aren't strong enough," Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati told reporters.   \par \par \uc2 Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Boediono expressed assurances that the government would continue to keep a close watch on the subprime loan situation.   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) officials had previously said they expected the global market \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be temporary and not have too much of an adverse effect on the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , saying the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would help contain the situation within its monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  authority.   \par \par \uc2 The local financial markets may indeed be waiting -- for better or for worse -- to see how BI follows up on its rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which will be decided during the next \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  meeting this Tuesday.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's benchmark BI rate currently stands at 8.25 percent. Chances are it will be held off from further trims due to July's inflation figure reaching 0.72 percent or 6.06 percent year-on-year. Another rate cut may further lessen the attractiveness of rupiah-based assets amid the current market slump.   \par \par \uc2 Markets may also watch for the soundness of state finances, with the government and the House of Representative's \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  Commission agreeing Monday on a revised \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  for this year of Rp 58.2 trillion (US$6.4 billion), or 1.54 percent of gross domestic product (GDP). This is slightly lower than a 1.7 percent of GDP the government had proposed in its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  revision.   \par \par \uc2 Inflation, meanwhile, is still expected to reach around 6.5 percent for the year, while the rupiah may average at Rp 9,050. The interest rate on BI's 3-month bills is assumed to be 8 percent in the revised \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070807e38700003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
