\par\par \b \uc2 BI holds benchmark rate steady at 8.25%   \b0\par\par\uc2 Urip Hudiono , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 502 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 August 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has put a halt on its recent rate cuts, anticipating more inflation and risks to the rupiah from current jitters in the global market.   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's (BI) Board of Governors decided in its monthly \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  meeting Tuesday to keep its benchmark interest rate at 8.25 percent, a level deemed level appropriate for promoting more bank lending.   \par \par \uc2 The rate hold is also aimed at helping the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continue expanding by 6.2 percent this year and 6.5 percent by 2008.   \par \par \uc2 Although BI believes inflation can still be maintained within the 5 to 7 percent range, recent volatility in financial markets worldwide has been a major consideration for its latest \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  decision.   \par \par \uc2 "BI will closely monitor developments to do with this situation and anticipate any potential effects on the inflation target and growth momentum," the Board said in a statement after the meeting.   \par \par \uc2 "BI will also continue to keep a close watch on global risks which could affect the stability of the macroeconomy and the financial sector. Capital flows dominated by short-term portfolio investments are among such risks."   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been trimming its BI rate since May last year from 12.75 percent, only pausing twice in June last year and April this year on inflation uptick trends. Inflation rose to 6.06 percent in July, from 5.77 percent in June.   \par \par \uc2 Analysts welcomed BI's latest decision, saying it had fulfilled market expectations by maintaining a balance not only between inflation concerns and growth prospects, but also taking into account investor confidence in the rupiah and assets based on the currency.   \par \par \uc2 Local shares and the rupiah have recently been under pressure from global market wobbles caused by \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over U.S. subprime loans. The rupiah weakened to an average of Rp 9,215 to the U.S. dollar in July, down from Rp 9,035 in June.   \par \par \uc2 "Holding the BI rate is in line with inflation trend expectations and keeping the rupiah attractive," Standard Chartered Indonesia chief economist Fauzi Ichsan told The Jakarta Post . "A weaker rupiah could fuel imported inflation, particularly when many goods still have imported contents of between 60 and 70 percent. BI can still cut rates later on, but perhaps more carefully."   \par \par \uc2 BNI senior economist Ryan Kiryanto said holding the BI rate was appropriate in light of continued rising inflation expected for August.   \par \par \uc2 He said the 8.25 percent rate was enough to keep rupiah-based assets attractive in comparison to U.S. assets.   \par \par \uc2 The U.S. Federal Reserve's key rate is currently 5.25 percent.   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Stock Exchange Composite Index closed 0.7 percent lower Tuesday to 2,174.07 points, little affected by the BI rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and still moving mostly on global market concerns and the U.S. Federal Reserve's coming \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The rupiah also closed slightly weaker at Rp 9,330 a dollar from Monday's Rp 9,295.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070808e38800001\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
