\par\par \b \uc2 Financial market volatility: Don't predict it, play it   \b0\par\par\uc2 Ari Pitoyo, CFA , Head of research   \par \uc2 913 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 August 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 How should one regard market volatility? Is it a beast that needs to be understood and played with, or something to be predicted and managed?   \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Composite Index has given up all the gains it made during the past month. The index climbed from 2,189 on July 3 to a high of 2,401 on July 24, before plunging back to 2,189 on Aug. 6.   \par \par \uc2 Volatility was also felt in the bond market. The government bond index, which saw its peak on June 20 at 1,373, gradually declined to 1,355 on Aug. 2, while the price of the 10-year bond (FR028) fell off 3.2 percent from early June to 105.0 (yield to maturity 9.22%).   \par \par \uc2 As widely reported, the recent corrections follow woes in the U.S. subprime loan market and its ensuing effect on hedge fund losses.   \par \par \uc2 The impact was heightened as hedge funds, most being highly leveraged, have to cover losses amid a wave of redemptions. Many people ask: has this correction been overdone, will we see a rebound, what would happen next?   \par \par \uc2 I myself believe that it would be futile to make analyses and predictions of what will happen next or whether the market has reached the bottom. I prefer to ride the volatility and find good investments in the current beating. If no attractive investments are available, I refrain from entering even though prices have reached what technical analysts call the "bottom". So how does one spot a good investment?   \par \par \uc2 Liquidity, which has been propping up asset prices for some time, is now tightening. However we think liquidity, excluding leverage, is still growing healthily. According to the IMF, total foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  held by central banks around the world currently stand at the equivalent of around US$5 trillion, having more than doubled since 2002.   \par \par \uc2 As long as the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still growing, \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  will still expand and will need a place to be invested in. Liquidity will keep on rising unless U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are dramatically raised further; i.e. not just by a mere 25 to 100 basis points (bps).   \par \par \uc2 Already we see inflation lurking up. China, which used to export deflation to the rest of the world, is facing a potential spike in inflation as prices of pork surge. Chinese inflation rose to its highest level in more than two years in May, with food prices jumping 8.3 percent from a year ago. Meat prices jumped 26.5 percent, while the cost of eggs was up 37.1 percent. China is expected to export inflation in the future.   \par \par \uc2 Current safety concern over Chinese products will add a safety premium that may translate into higher costs. Environmental damage will also add another cost component.   \par \par \uc2 As inflation emerges, asset prices also adjust. This partly explains the recent surge in M&A activity, as buyers benefit from low \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to purchase assets whose values are expected to increase in the future. Despite the recent rise in risk aversion, cash is still not a safe investment in a rising inflation environment. World \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth will prevail despite the recent subprime troubles.   \par \par \uc2 News regarding online tutors from India for U.S. students is an interesting piece of anecdotal evidence to observe. With information technology we will see a more balanced world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in which wages, currently expensive on one side of the world, become streamlined. As China and India grow, so will other Asian countries; this will strengthen demand for commodities.   \par \par \uc2 This sums up what we believe will be the long-term trends. Recent shocks in global markets might present opportunities to cherry-pick investments that could provide us with a hedge from inflation.   \par \par \uc2 Energy stocks would be one example. It is difficult to envisage a sustained downtrend in energy prices in the future. Simple statistics from BP could explain this in a simple way. The U.S. consumes energy at more than 6 tons oil equivalent per capita, while China and India's consumption levels are still at 0-1.5 tons oil equivalent per capita. The incremental demand for energy will be enormous if China's energy consumption per capita reaches, say, just half of that in the U.S.   \par \par \uc2 Another asset class worth watching is property, especially those properties that produce commodities that are high in demand. Global warming will increase weather unpredictability, adding \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  premiums to current prices.   \par \par \uc2 We should long for a heavy correction in commodity stocks. The recent run in mining, agriculture and property stocks have put them on an expensive valuation, which if corrected could give a good opportunity for entry.   \par \par \uc2 There are other possibilities, but our broad guideline is aiming for fixed-asset-laden stocks or other investment vehicles. Therefore once again we would prefer to play the volatility, not predict it.   \par \par \uc2 Few are equipped with the ability to foresee the next spike or crash in the index. What we can do is judge whether an investment makes sense; i.e. whether it would provide us with a return that matches our risk-taking profile.   \par \par \uc2 The recent shocks reflect the market's increased perception of risk. This appears to be just a correction after a period of inflated optimism. Sentiments sway from one extreme to the other from time to time.