 \highlight\uc2  barriers.   \par \par \uc2 The deal, which included an agreement around the environmental and health sectors, would potentially open the door for an influx of investment from Japan.   \par \par \uc2 However, several experts and businesspeople said it would remain difficult to export Indonesian products to Japan because of the country's notorious non-\b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  barriers.   \par \par \uc2 East Asian expert at the Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) Begi Hersutanto said Indonesia must focus on domestic issues and stop complaining about Japan's expansion in Indonesian markets.   \par \par \uc2 "We can't blame Japan for using us as a market," Begi said.   \par \par \uc2 "We have failed because we don't have a national synergy to create resilience as a nation.   \par \par \uc2 "For instance, there is no convergent strategy from government, businesspeople or civil society to raise our competitiveness.   \par \par \uc2 "We should do it now, although it's a little too late."   \par \par \uc2 He said if Indonesia had a united voice at a national level, the country could push Japan to open up its markets for Indonesia's agricultural products.   \par \par \uc2 "With Japan depending on our gas and oil supply as well as our strategic position in ASEAN (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations), Japan needs us more than we need them," Begi said.   \par \par \uc2 "We have sufficient bargaining position to persuade Japan to open its markets if we are united to push for one convergent \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia is Japan's biggest gas supplier and major oil provider.   \par \par \uc2 Abe said a stable supply of natural gas would be the foundation for bilateral cooperation between the two countries.   \par \par \uc2 Theo and Begi said Abe's visit also underscored Indonesia's strategic position as ASEAN's biggest country and a balancing player in the region.   \par \pa