\par\par \b \uc2 The critical threat of earthquakes   \b0\par\par\uc2 Bantarto Bandoro , Jakarta   \par \uc2 670 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 September 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Natural disasters are always a test of our capacity to empathize with other people's suffering, and the recent earthquake in Bengkulu and in Yogyakarta in May last year are no exception.   \par \par \uc2 Protecting ourselves against powerful earthquakes is clearly a real challenge, but perhaps it would be wise to consider which resources should be devoted to protecting housing and infrastructure from the inevitable earthquakes in the future.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia is prone to a range of natural and man-made disasters, including droughts, forest fires, floods, earthquakes, landslides, volcanic eruptions and tsunamis.   \par \par \uc2 With a string of earthquakes and tsunamis over the last four years, the latest Bengkulu earthquake is a reminder of the many perils facing the archipelago.   \par \par \uc2 While the recent earthquake was reported to have claimed 17 lives and injured 88 ( The Jakarta Post online, Sept. 15), which is far less than the 2006 Yogyakarta earthquake, it destroyed many homes and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  facilities.   \par \par \uc2 This type of disaster requires immediate attention because without relief operations, conditions can deteriorate rapidly. Following the quake in Bengkulu, governments and the international community showed their support in their prompt aid for the victims ( The Jakarta Post , Sept. 15).   \par \par \uc2 However, a report three days after the earthquake claimed that people directly affected by the disaster were receiving insufficient attention and care. Claims that several quake-hit areas were missed by relief operations have frustrated some quake victims. The subsequent spread of various diseases and a complete breakdown of local infrastructure have caused more difficulties to Bengkulu than the earthquake itself.   \par \par \uc2 Earthquakes can and do happen anytime and anywhere. Because of their unpredictability, earthquakes are difficult to pinpoint as potential hazards or threats. Yogyakarta and Central Java, for example, are not recorded as earthquake-prone areas.   \par \par \uc2 When threats are realized or actualized, they are acknowledged as hazards. Hazards are only potential disasters, not actual disasters themselves. A hazard or threat does not necessarily harm people. Experience has shown us that earthquake areas including Bengkulu were not made aware of either an earthquake threat or hazard, as the earthquakes came unanticipated. The Meteorology and Geophysics Agency failed to anticipate the earthquake in Bengkulu or warn its people of the danger.   \par \par \uc2 This earthquake put human security in jeopardy. Particularly in areas hit most severely by the earthquake, people have come into contact with hazards. What has occurred can no longer be called a security threat or hazard, but a security disaster for those involved.   \par \par \uc2 Bengkulu people have experienced misery and suffering and some have lost their lives. The fact that many people have been left temporarily or permanently homeless, may be forced to live in tents for an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  period or may have not received medical care breaches basic human security needs.   \par \par \uc2 Human beings are victims in every type of disaster, whether it be flooding, landslides or earthquakes. In an event such as an earthquake, safety must be made the priority of relief operations. Exposure to the effects of the disaster should be minimized to guarantee the future well-being of victims.   \par \par \uc2 The suddenness of the Bengkulu earthquake and the tragedies it has caused have disrupted many people's lives. The possibility of future earthquakes is an additional concern for the earthquake sufferers.   \par \par \uc2 In an event like the Bengkulu earthquake, efforts made by relief organizations to enhance security for those in need must also take into account other areas which have a direct impact on human security, namely: \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  security, food security, health security and environmental security.   \par \par \uc2 Perhaps then, the issue of security following a disaster such as this is not the responsibility of the state or the nation, but rather individuals and people. Those involved in relief operations need to prescribe to such a perspective.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is chief editor of The Indonesian Quarterly published by the Centre for Strategic and International Studies. He is also a lecturer in the International Relations Postgraduate Studies Program at the University of Indonesia, Jakarta. He can be contacted at bandoro@csis.or.id.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070920e39k0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
