\par\par \b \uc2 Watching the oil-price hike   \b0\par\par\uc2 769 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 September 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The government has assured the general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  the steady oil price-hike that started early this year -- and which progressed to more than US$80/barrel over the past few days -- would not have an adverse impact on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 On average, according to chief economics minister Boediono, oil prices between January and the middle of this month were still around the $60 average assumed for the 2007 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  estimates.   \par \par \uc2 Even if the oil prices remained above $80 for the rest of the year, the impact on \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  management would still be well under control, because the increase in gasoline \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , estimated at Rp 56.4 trillion ($6.06 billion) for this year, would be offset by rises in government revenues from oil exports.   \par \par \uc2 But problems would arise if oil prices remained above $80 or even continued to rise next year, because the $60 average oil price assumed for the 2008 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year would have to be reviewed.   \par \par \uc2 It's needless to remind the government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , currently deliberating the 2008 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  proposal, they should closely and carefully monitor the international oil price developments before deciding the average oil price assumed for the next \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year.   \par \par \uc2 The Rp 46.70 trillion appropriation proposed for fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  next year has been estimated on an average oil price of $60.   \par \par \uc2 It is always difficult to predict the direction of oil prices because there are so many \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and non-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  factors that influence this commodity. But is nevertheless worthy to note the OPEC (Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries) decision last week to expand their daily production quota by 500,000 barrels or 2 percent seemed not able -- at least until last week -- to press down oil prices to below $80.   \par \par \uc2 Energy analysts have mixed views about the oil price movements. Several forecast a downward trend within weeks due to the foreseen weakening \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the United States, as an impact of the recent sub-prime mortgage crisis.   \par \par \uc2 However, the Federal Reserve's decision early last week to lower its benchmark interest rate by a half percentage point to 4.75 could still generate a moderate growth in the American \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The easing of the money \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , combined with an earlier reduction in the discount rate -- the direct loans the Fed makes to banks -- from 5.75 percent to 5.15 percent, is expected to limit the damage from the recent disorder in the housing and credit markets.   \par \par \uc2 But many analysts no longer calculate the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition in the U.S as the biggest factor influencing international oil prices. After the emergence of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  star China, with an annual growth of more than 9 percent and India, the oil market has been influenced heavily by these two economies.   \par \par \uc2 Quite a number of petroleum analysts think oil prices will remain over $70 for the rest of the year -- or may even climb to almost $90-95 later this year, because China and India will most likely continue to enjoy robust growth next year, further fueling their seemingly unstoppable demand for oil.   \par \par \uc2 These analysts argue OPEC will not allow oil prices far over $80, fearing dearer oil will cut \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth -- and over the longer term, consumers respond to higher prices by driving more efficient cars and substituting other fuels for petrol.   \par \par \uc2 High prices also are bound to constrain demand and cause \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth unpredictably, while Middle Eastern politics make the future of both demand and supply \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Which ever of the analysts' predictions comes true, the blunt reality businesses will have to live with is the era of costly oil is here to stay.   \par \par \uc2 In fact, businesses will have to bear the brunt as immediately next month, if the current prices ($80) remain steady, because unlike gasoline and kerosene for household use, domestic fuel prices for industrial users are floating on market prices in Singapore.   \par \par \uc2 Yet another damaging impact of this costlier oil will be dearer hydrocarbon-based products including plastics and synthetic fibers, which in turn will increase the costs of packaging materials and textiles etc.   \par \par \uc2 So even though the impact of the oil price movements is still rather neutral on the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  management side, the government should closely monitor the repercussions of the costlier oil on the various categories of industries in a bid to curb inflationary pressures.   \par \par \uc2 Stronger inflationary pressures may abort a further decrease in \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's benchmark interest rate, currently 8.25 percent, which is now widely expected by businesspeople after the U.S Fed cuts its fund rate to 4.75 percent early last week.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070924e39o0000