\par\par \b \uc2 BI and the rate cuts   \b0\par\par\uc2 Winarno Zain , Jakarta   \par \uc2 975 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 September 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Following the U.S. Federal Reserve decision to lower its benchmark interest rate by 50 basis points to 4.75 percent on Sept. 18, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , will have to decide whether to cut its benchmark rate or to maintain it at the current level of 8.25 percent. The answer will depend on whether BI believes inflationary pressures are still on the rise or whether they have subsided.   \par \par \uc2 It will also depend on BI's view of whether \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and employment creation have to take precedence over containing inflation. Like central banks all over the world, for BI, the question of containing inflation and reviving \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth always seem to be a question of "either/or". One can only be achieved at the expense of the other.   \par \par \uc2 The U.S. Federal Reserve decision to make a significant cut in its interest rate clearly showed that it is seriously concerned with the slowdown in the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  resulting from the sub-prime housing loan crisis.   \par \par \uc2 Previously, the Fed was obsessed with containing inflation, which is still above the "comfort zone", despite low \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Hence the tight monetary stance by the Fed for the last two years. The bold decision that the Fed has taken looked like a preemptive measure to prevent the mortgage crisis hurting the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  too much.   \par \par \uc2 As the slowdown in the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could drag down economies in Asia, including the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the preemptive measure taken by the Fed mean that central banks in Asia, including \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , have been somewhat let off the hook as regards taking similar measures. From this angle, it could be said that even if BI did not lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the downside risk for the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from the weakening of the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been partly taken care by the Fed.   \par \par \uc2 BI could still consider lowering \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in order to seize the momentum provided by the loosening of monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by the Fed, or because of the mounting pressure from the government and business community. However, the question is whether further monetary loosening by BI could spark higher inflation?   \par \par \uc2 It is important to note that inflationary pressures have not softened, but have been on the rise instead. Inflation in the last three months showed that both core inflation and volatile food prices have been less affected by cyclical influences, but rather have undergone changes that are structural in nature.   \par \par \uc2 The rise in import prices have not only been due to the depreciation of the rupiah in recent months, but are also due to inflation in the countries of origin, resulting from higher oil prices. Food prices, which increased 11 percent year-on-year in July, are a reflection of a structural shift in the supply-demand relationship. Various factors have adversely affected the domestic supply.   \par \par \uc2 The fight against bird flu has eliminated thousands of small-scale poultry businesses; the lack of crude palm oil for domestic cooking oil production has resulted in steep price increases; and bad weather disrupted the operation of the fishing fleet for several months, which affected the seafood supply all over the country. Weather experts predict that because of climate changes, the occurrence of unfavorable weather will be recurrent phenomenon, and this will definitely have repercussions for food production.   \par \par \uc2 Inflationary pressures will also come from increased government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the end of this year and next year. Both the central government and local governments have been under pressure to speed up \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  after a slow start at the beginning of the year.   \par \par \uc2 A higher \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  that will reach 1.7 percent of GDP next year will cause undue monetary expansion and upward inflationary pressure, and therefore should be watched carefully by BI. A survey of inflationary expectation for the next 3 to 6 months conducted by BI among retail traders and consumers also showed higher anticipated inflation.   \par \par \uc2 Money in circulation increased sharply in July, with M1 and M2 rising by 16 percent (y-on-y) and 10 percent (y-on-y), respectively from 9.7 percent and 6.6 percent the previous month.   \par \par \uc2 Bank lending growth, which was a source of concern early in the year, rose to 19 percent (y-on-y) in July, compared with 14 percent at the beginning of the year, surpassing the 15 percent growth in deposits. The usual increased liquidity in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the middle of Ramadhan and over the upcoming Idul Fitri festivities does not bode well for a looser monetary stance by BI.   \par \par \uc2 There is even a case for an interest rate increase given the rising inflationary pressures. But given the current condition of the global market, such action could produce undesirable consequences. Increasing rates could increase capital inflows and further strengthen the rupiah, but the dampening effect on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth could undermine market confidence once the slowdown extends into the entire \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 So, despite increasing upward pressure on inflation, tightening monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  at this stage by BI could undermine macroeconomic stability. Experience over the last two months shows that even when BI kept its interest rate on hold, it did not have a significant effect on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding the effects of the home mortgage maelstrom in the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  persist. The extent of the real damage in the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not yet fully known and it is possible that the worst is not yet over.   \par \par \uc2 It would be better, therefore, for BI to follow the example of central banks in other countries: Wait until a clearer picture emerges. Until then, maintaining the benchmark rate at its current level seems to the most sensible thing to do.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  analyst. He can be reached at winarno_zain@yahoo.com.sg.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020070927e39r0000m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
