\par\par \b \uc2 Future perfect reform of investment regime   \b0\par\par\uc2 Wayne Forrest , New York   \par \uc2 830 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 October 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Indonesian leaders often phrase their reform policies with future perfect verb constructions. "We intend to revise the labor laws," or "We will cut bureaucratic red tape and judicial corruption," or "We will abolish local \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  that contravene national contracts," or "We will clarify the list of sectors closed to foreign investment," or "We hope to revise labor laws to make them business friendly."   \par \par \uc2 These statements tempt companies with visions the investment climate has finally caught up with their desire to participate in Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. But, at its midway point and in spite of a spate of news articles to the contrary, the Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono administration, its many successes aside, has yet to seriously attract new European and American "greenfield" investors. Has the reform agenda run out of steam or are nationalist impulses winning over reformers?   \par \par \uc2 On the bright side, China, Japan, and also Russia and Middle East countries have booked significant investment tied to natural resources. Some infrastructure investment has been pledged using government facilities from these same countries, reminiscent of Japanese tied aid investment of the 70s and 80s.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  statements have been helpful in courting portfolio and currency investors while keeping direct investors, vital to creating sustained growth for the future, hanging around.   \par \par \uc2 A new investment law, falling \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , strong telecommunications sector and robust commodity exports have boosted confidence and growth rates (projected to be 6.3 percent in 2007). Interestingly, much of this growth is in provinces away from Jakarta, a sign of the benefits of the government's decentralization \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Corruptors continue to be prosecuted and anti-terrorism cooperation has been a success. Since 1998, Indonesia has recovered and the normal issues of a democratic country (governance, justice, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  well being) rather than stability and violence are uppermost.   \par \par \uc2 But if you only scratch the surface one begins to see a different picture. For example, a recent World Bank survey indicates the average start-up time for a new business actually increased from 97 to 105 days since last year. Cumbersome procedures, judicial malfeasance and a rigid labor law continue to discourage manufacturing investment. Consequently, employment and poverty rates have not improved. The new investment law mandating equal treatment between local and foreign companies does not seem to apply to all investors. An updated negative investment list, while more transparent, inexplicably reduces foreign equity positions in areas such as transportation, telecommunications, insurance and pharmaceuticals.   \par \par \uc2 Significant new direct investment in mining (where the country has a distinct advantage) has not materialized. Drilling rates are also down in the oil patch. A perception of contract and regulatory \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  persists. New proposals circulating -- if adopted -- would require more local processing and shares for local firms and regional governments. Why invest in exploration if you are not sure your contract will be renewed or if the system governing your initial contract will suddenly change? Compounding the paralysis is the fact that many companies just don't explore anymore so that no new major mineral discoveries have been announced in over ten years. For similar reasons, Indonesia's crude oil production has dropped. If the government adequately focused on mining and energy Indonesia would be reaping huge additional rewards from sky high commodity prices.   \par \par \uc2 As a further distraction, the growing separation of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and private sector affairs has created a revenue gap for the bureaucracy. There are rumblings some functionaries are moving to regain marginal government control over certain key sectors when they should be accelerating \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms needed to attract a more diversified base of private, direct investment.   \par \par \uc2 While the Indonesian government should be credited with the return of investment pledges and approvals to pre-1998 levels, it must appreciate that much of the investment is not on fully commercial terms. Many of the Chinese, Russian and Japanese offers to build power plants or toll roads require government financial guarantees or utilize mixed credits and merit only short-term optimism. If only those countries that have a strong strategic interest in ensuring energy or commodity supplies are investors can Indonesia be satisfied?   \par \par \uc2 In order to firmly secure the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability so vital to ensure its hard-fought democratic gains, Indonesia must create an investment regime attractive to investors from all countries based on mutually beneficial long-term commercial motivations rather than politically expedient deals.   \par \par \uc2 We are living in a time of unprecedented worldwide liquidity searching for productive investment locations. But this window will not stay open long and it will take more than good intentions for Indonesia to grab its share. Without more open and aggressive laws and policies to fix the investment climate and absent a steady promotional campaign in major markets such as the U.S. to announce these achievements, it may be several decades before this chance returns.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is President of the American Indonesian Chamber of Commerce (AICC). The views represented above do not necessarily reflect those of AICC members.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020071024e3ao0000o\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Fed Rate Cut to Boost Stock Market   \b0\par\par\uc2 390 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 October 2007\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The US Federal Reserve's decision on interest rate and the publication of the data on October's inflation this week will determine the movement of the stock exchange. Analysts expect both factors will go as expected. The interest of investors in newly listed stocks, such as Wijaya Karya that will be listed today, will also be crucial to the market.   \par \par \uc2 In addition, the auction of FR0047-series and FR0048-series T-bonds by the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) on Tuesday is expected to stimulate the bond market.   \par \par \uc2 Analyst at Finan Securities Teuku Hendry Andrean estimated the volatility of the Composite Stock Price Index (IHSG) this week would still be high in the wake of global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The Fed, he continued, was expected to cut its rate to create certainty and to boost IHSG on the Jakarta Stock Exchange this week. "The market players hope The Fed again cuts its rate following unpromising data on house sales."   \par \par \uc2 Data by the US showed that only 770,000 units of houses in September were sold or 4.8%, down from 735,000 units or 7.9% in August.   \par \par \uc2 Survey by Bloomberg of some economists and analysts exposed that they expected the Fed Rate to be cut by 25 basis points (bps) to 4.50%. A separate survey disclosed that the domestic inflation rate in October would reach 0.71%, down from 0.80% in September.   \par \par \uc2 According to Teuku, if the Fed's decision was positively welcomed, the index could soar to 2,700, surpassing the highest resistance level of 2,661. He also warned of the signs for bubble index due to the reactive market.   \par \par \uc2 The Federal Open Market Committee schedules to have its meeting on October 31 and Indoensia can only know the result of the meeting on Wednesday night, when the stock market will have already been closed. Therefore, investors can only use the result of the meeting as a factor to make investments on Thursday (November 1).   \par \par \uc2 As usual, the Central Bureau for Statistics (BPS) at the beginning of every month announces data on the previous month's inflation. Bond analyst at Panin Sekuritas Benjamin Siahaan disclosed the inflation rate in October was predicted at 0.5%-0.6% and that would be goods news to the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . (Bisnis/pul)   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020071029e3at00002\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Oil Production in 2008 May Miss the Target due to Soaring Oil Price   \b0\par\par\uc2 486 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 October 2007\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Indonesia will probably fail to meet its oil production target in 2008 due to the soaring international oil price and the high-risk character of oil fields in the country.   \par \par \uc2 Deputy Head of the Oil and Gas Upstream Activities Executive Agency (BP Migas) Abdul Mu'in revealed the soaring oil price would increase project activities, boost production costs, and tighten competition for project gears and infrastructures.   \par \par \uc2 If oil and gas companies failed to get the required gears, he continued, some oil and gas projects had to be delayed for years.   \par \par \uc2 "So, the major repercussion of the soaring oil price is the high number of oil and gas projects delayed, which will certainly affect our country's oil and gas production," he explained yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 An oil and gas company, he inserted, usually had many projects in different countries, but no sufficient manpower and gears. As a result, he added, the company had to be selective to cut projects that would not be feasible to develop.   \par \par \uc2 "Indonesia is one of the countries that may face a threat of seeing many of their oil and gas projects delayed."   \par \par \uc2 According to him, it would be difficult to meet the target to produce 1.084 million barrels of oil per day in 2008 since some projects in Indonesia could be categorized as high-risk and expensive projects. The political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , political risks (including \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies), and technical risks in Indonesia also exacerbate the situation.   \par \par \uc2 The government itself has approved 20 plans of development (PoD) until 2010 consisting of 10 PoDs for 2007, nine PoDs for 2008, and one PoD for 2009.   \par \par \uc2 In addition, there are 19 additional PoDs recommended to be started in 2008 -2009, EOR programs in 39 fields and tenders for 26 working regions recommended to be run in 2007, and tenders for 40 working regions per annum starting from 2008.   \par \par \uc2 Projects Prioritized to Cut   \par \par \uc2 Abdul Mu'in further revealed the exploration activities in new fields and the oil and gas projects in deep sea would be projects prioritized to cut by oil and gas companies.   \par \par \uc2 However, he said that almost all countries were facing the same threat of being unable to meet their oil production targets. "So, we should not be surprised if we cannot meet our oil production target. This is not something now."   \par \par \uc2 When asked for his comment, a researcher at the Institute for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Social Research, Education, and Information (LP3ES) Pri Agung Rakhmanto admitted it would be difficult to meet the target to produce 1.084 million barrels of oil per day.   \par \par \uc2 However, he exposed the difficulty was caused by the fact that some of the existing oil and gas fields were old and were difficult to produce much oil in a short time and by some operational issues, such as incomplete land acquisition process in Cepu Block. (Bisnis/raf)   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020071030e3au00005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
