\par\par \b \uc2 High-flying oil prices: Would $100 a barrel be good for us?   \b0\par\par\uc2 Helmi Arman , Analyst   \par \uc2 956 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 October 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's trade position is much more resilient today against skyrocketing oil prices. But still, expensive oil exposes the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to risks that are clearly undesirable.   \par \par \uc2 As widely reported, the prices of benchmark crude oil recently reached a record high of over US$93 per barrel following continuing supply concerns amid heightening tensions in the Middle East.   \par \par \uc2 Given declining global production and rising demand from China, it's admittedly difficult to envisage a scenario where high oil prices aren't here to stay. This leads us to one important question: how will Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  be impacted by soaring oil prices? Should we cheer or jeer?   \par \par \uc2 Thus far, accounts from various sources quoted by the media have been conflicting and are often confusing for the average individual.   \par \par \uc2 On one hand we have officials emphasizing the oil profit windfall and downplaying the potential threats, while on the other hand skeptics seem to have been scaremongering over the prospect of a depreciating rupiah, wider \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and rising inflation.   \par \par \uc2 Which views should we accept? First, let's discuss the exchange rate outlook. Why is it that we haven't seen the rupiah going into free fall to the same degree as seen back in 2005 when oil prices surged to then record highs?   \par \par \uc2 Back then, Indonesia was a net oil importer, and higher oil prices led to a deterioration in the country's trade balance. This, in turn, precipitated a weakening of the rupiah, which was exacerbated by an outflow of foreign capital from the domestic bond market.   \par \par \uc2 Today we're still a net oil importer. In fact, August data shows the oil-trade \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  amounting to US$5.4 billion this year, a 5 percent increase from 2006. However the situation for the overall trade balance has changed. Prices of non-oil commodities have also been rising. This is beneficial since Indonesia is a net exporter of non-oil commodities, e.g., coal, palm oil, tin, etc.   \par \par \uc2 The figures show that since 2005, the trade surplus in non-oil commodities has widened by an extent that is greater than the deterioration experienced in the oil-trade \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Up to July 2007, the excess of the former over the latter amounted to around US$1.5 billion per month by our count, up from just $850 million in October, 2005.   \par \par \uc2 However, this doesn't mean we are immune from exchange rate fluctuations. The currency is still exposed to risks arising from capital flight. A rise in inflation expectations as a result of surging oil prices could cause bond yields to rise and trigger a sell-off on the bond market.   \par \par \uc2 As historical data shows, rising yields in the bond market are highly correlated with swings in the exchange rate. Any sell-off by foreign investors would naturally be negative for the rupiah.   \par \par \uc2 So, just how high is the inflation risk and chances of another domestic fuel price increase taking place today?   \par \par \uc2 Many relate this to the resilience of the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  standing. In this regard, some misperceptions should be straightened out. Does it really matter whether rising oil prices widen or improve the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , or if the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  exceeds the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  target?   \par \par \uc2 As long as there's political will, the numbers in the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  can obviously be changed to suit prevailing conditions. We've seen this happen before. In 2005, the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  was revised not once, but twice at the end of the year to accommodate pressure from oil prices.   \par \par \uc2 And even if one thinks the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  is an issue, the government could always "reprioritize" its \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  account to prevent the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  from swelling. Again we saw this happen in 2005.   \par \par \uc2 So, \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  resilience doesn't seem to be the key risk here. Then what is? In our view, it's the scarcity risk!   \par \par \uc2 The amount of the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  paid on every liter of fuel sold to households rises along with the upward trend in international crude oil prices. Once this amount reaches a certain point, many will find it very profitable to hoard, smuggle or illegally redirect sales of subsidized fuels to the industrial sector.   \par \par \uc2 Substantial diversions of domestic supply could lead to fuel scarcities on the streets, a potential source of instability that can only be effectively addressed by one thing: reducing the disparity between subsidized and non-subsidized fuel prices, which logically can only be achieved by increasing the prices of the former.   \par \par \uc2 At what point will the scarcity risk become acute? Much will depend on the effectiveness of law enforcement. But in 2005 -- right before scarcities led to an increase in fuel prices -- subsidized diesel was selling at around Rp 3,300 per liter less than unsubsidized diesel. Today, the gap is Rp 2,700, but this is rising.   \par \par \uc2 So, regardless of what the official accounts say, is there a risk of oil prices being hiked? Yes.   \par \par \uc2 Many say there are two sides to every story. There certainly is. But unfortunately we haven't much space to discuss the benefits of rising prosperity in commodity-producing regions. Nor is there room to analyze the benefits of the faster increase in foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a result of the bigger trade surplus.   \par \par \uc2 At the end of the day, it all comes down to whether or not we will be willing to see the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery put on the line by the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  arising from surging oil prices.   \par \par \uc2 Regardless of improvements in the trade balance and despite what many say about the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , a fuel price hike may be lurking around the corner. Oil at $100 would definitely bring that corner closer.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020071031e3av0001a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
