\par\par \b \uc2 The writing on the wall   \b0\par\par\uc2 720 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 November 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  seems to have increasingly suffered from the steep rise in international oil prices, the utterly slow pace of new investment and the weakening of global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.   \par \par \uc2 Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati warned on Wednesday that our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth for the whole year could reach only 6.2 percent, 10 basis points lower than the 6.3 percent target, due mainly to a slow pace of new investment by both the government and private sector.   \par \par \uc2 Many had earlier expected much higher growth of up to 6.5 percent after the first half posted a 6.1 percent expansion, but we now seemed to have lost the momentum for robust growth.   \par \par \uc2 Certainly, 6.2 percent growth is still highly respectable and 70 basis points higher than last year's 5.5 percent expansion. However, that pace of growth is far from adequate to address the almost 12 percent unemployment rate, not to mention the estimated 30 million under-employed and the 2.5 million new job seekers entering the labor market annually.   \par \par \uc2 Investment growth for the year is now estimated to be 2.3 percentage points below the 12.3 percent target. As of last month, the government succeeded in realizing only some 47 percent of its investment \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  budgeted for this year. It would be rather impossible for the government to implement the remaining 53 percent of its investment \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the remaining two months. This is especially bad news for the overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  efficiency because the bulk of the investment funds has been allocated for basic infrastructure which have crumbled due to lack of maintenance over the past 10 years.   \par \par \uc2 Private investment performed even worse as most foreign investors still prefer waiting on the sidelines.   \par \par \uc2 We don't expect a better outlook for next year as new factors of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- the devastating impact of the sub-prime mortgage crisis in the United States, weakening global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and skyrocketing oil prices -- have gripped the whole \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Sri Mulyani tried to calm down the market, asserting that the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  could still be controlled at 1.5 percent of the gross domestic product this year with \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  cuts and efficiency measures despite the almost 50 percent increase in fuel and electricity \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 However, the market is waiting for more credible and sustainable contingency measures on the part of the government to cope with the cascading impact of a weakening global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, the sub-prime mortgage financial crisis in the U.S and much costlier oil.   \par \par \uc2 Positive market perception of the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  management is even more vital now because the government has increasingly depended on bond flotation to plug its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  hole.   \par \par \uc2 It is futile for the government to expect significant falls in oil prices within the next few weeks or months, despite the weakening world \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth because, unlike in the 20th century, the main driver of oil demand now is no longer the American \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  but China and India which are projected to continue expanding by 9-10 percent a year.   \par \par \uc2 Most analysts agree that as oil prices will remain high and continue their upward trend it is imperative for the government to step up measures to improve energy efficiency and conservation. For governments which still subsidize fuel prices, it is now the right time to let market forces govern oil prices and protect the poor people from the impact of costlier oil with social safety-net programs.   \par \par \uc2 Maintaining domestic fuel prices far below international prices will discourage investment in alternative, renewable energy and energy-efficient machinery and make export smuggling much more attractive.   \par \par \uc2 In fact, fuel smuggling overseas might have already occurred. The latest government estimate put fuel consumption this year at almost 7 percent higher than the earlier estimate while the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is lower than the original target. Where did the additional fuel go?   \par \par \uc2 Postponing bold measures in the hope that oil prices will again stabilize at a lower range would only accumulate problems and heighten the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the adjustments that have eventually to be made -- like the 125 percent fuel price rise in October 2005 -- will be quite massive, abrupt and certainly very painful.   \par \par \uc2 It is much better, less painful and less costly to absorb the oil price shocks gradually through the market mechanism.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020071115e3bf0000m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
