\par\par \b \uc2 Oil prices to remain 'crazy': Soebroto   \b0\par\par\uc2 Riyadi Suparno , The Jakarta Post, Riyadh   \par \uc2 630 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 November 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Oil prices will remain "crazy" for the next few months, or even years, as consuming countries demand more supplies, while the Organization of Petroleum Producing Countries (OPEC) wants security of demand to increase output.   \par \par \uc2 Speaking at a symposium ahead of the 3rd OPEC Summit here, former OPEC secretary-general Soebroto predicted that oil prices, currently hovering around $90 per barrel, would likely rise again in the near future and hit the psychological level of US$100.   \par \par \uc2 "Is it likely that oil will reach $100? The answer is yes. There are three issues contributing to this, namely, the drawdown in U.S. crude oil stocks, the coming winter and the weakening of the U.S. dollar," Soebroto said.   \par \par \uc2 He predicted that crude oil prices would stay high in the near future and then find new stability in line with supply and demand in the longer term.   \par \par \uc2 In the shorter term, demand will remain strong, especially from emerging economies such as China and India. However, in the longer term, the slowdown in the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would affect demand. Also China and India would not continue to grow at their current levels of 9 to 10 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Robert Mabro, from the Oxford Institute for Energy Studies, noted that oil prices are not determined by supply and demand alone. Prices were even beyond the control of the oil producing countries, and were much more determined by players in the financial markets.   \par \par \uc2 "We cannot rely on price regimes. It's just totally crazy. One day it's near $100, and 10 years ago it was $10," Mabro said.   \par \par \uc2 A number of factors are contributing to this, including constraints on investment faced by both international and national oil companies, he said.   \par \par \uc2 International companies are hostages to their shareholders who demand extremely high rates of return on investment, while national oil companies face financial problems.   \par \par \uc2 There were also political constraints hampering a number of oil producing countries from increasing output. Sanctions imposed on Iran, and in the past on Iraq and Libya, had reduced their capacities to invest.   \par \par \uc2 While supplies are \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , demand is rising in line with growing demand for energy to fuel world \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, with fossil fuels expected to continue dominating the energy landscape until 2050.   \par \par \uc2 According to Mohammed Hamel, head of OPEC's Energy Studies Department, demand for crude oil would increase by 35 million barrel per day (bpd) to about 110 million bpd by 2030. Most demand would still come from the developed countries.   \par \par \uc2 OPEC, currently supplying 30 million bpd out of the world's total demand of 84 million bpd, will play an increasingly important role in meeting future demand for oil as its member states control 78 percent of the world's existing oil \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 OPEC secretary-general Abdullah Al-Badri noted that oil producing countries would invest more to increase production only if there was a security of demand.   \par \par \uc2 With current demand trends, Al-Badri said that OPEC member states would be investing up to US$150 billion in 120 projects to produce 19 million bpd by 2015.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesian Minister of Energy and Mineral Resources Purnomo Yusgiantoro revealed Thursday that the country aimed to increase output to slightly over 1 million bpd, from the current level of slightly above 900,000 bpd.   \par \par \uc2 As of last September, Indonesia had been producing oil at below the 900,000 level, the smallest output in OPEC, besides Qatar.   \par \par \uc2 Robert Mabro noted that the easiest way to boost OPEC production would be to increase output in Saudi Arabia.   \par \par \uc2 "Saudi could produce much more (than its current level of around 8 to 9 million bpd), but do you really want it? Surely not sustainable when huge extra oil supplies come onstream."   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020071116e3bg00015\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Index to be Consolidated, T-bonds Prices May Increase again   \b0\par\par\uc2 398 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 November 2007\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The stock market this week is estimated to be consolidated (move flat), while the T-bonds market is predicted to be more stable, making the prices of the securities instrument to possibly increase again.   \par \par \uc2 Head of Research at Mega Capital Indonesia Felix Sindhunata revealed the market would still be consolidated and the Composite Stock Price Index (IHSG) on the Jakarta Stock Exchange (BEJ) was forecasted to hover at 2,630-2,730.   \par \par \uc2 The stock market will still monitor regional conditions, inflation, exchange rate, and the progress of the US subprime mortgage crisis that was potential to undermine the profits of some world financial companies.   \par \par \uc2 Amidst such condition, Felix told it would be difficult for investors to make daily trades. Therefore, he suggested them be more careful.   \par \par \uc2 "However, I think there will be no problems within the next six months. I am still optimistic about our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions," he said last weekend.   \par \par \uc2 Although IHSG last week fluctuated following regional and global sentiments, he viewed investors still had high confidence in the domestic market, so that the index remained high.   \par \par \uc2 The condition was not shared with the Dow Jones and Hang Seng indices that fell drastically. The Dow Jones index, which once hit over 14,000, on Friday dropped to 13.176, while the Hang Seng index, which once touched 31,600, declined to 27,614.   \par \par \uc2 More stable   \par \par \uc2 Separately, bond analyst at  \uc2 Trimegah Securities\uc2  Dian Abdul Hakim expected the bond market this week would be more stable, so that the yield curve could return to normal.   \par \par \uc2 "The current yield curve has increased from 9% to 9.4%. If investors can feel comfortable again, foreign investors will be interested in entering the bond market as well the stock market."   \par \par \uc2 According to Dian, the declining prices of T-bonds last week triggered the increases in the yields of bonds. Market players were worried that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 6.5% would boost inflation this month.   \par \par \uc2 The rising consumption to 70% of GDO was also worried to further increase inflation.   \par \par \uc2 If such condition happened, Dian added, it would be difficult for the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  (B) to cut its rate at its meeting on December 6. "Investors will feel that market conditions are still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , so that they will put their funds in short-term instruments, like in the money market." (Bisnis/pul)   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020071119e3bj00002\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
