\par\par \b \uc2 Barking up the wrong tree   \b0\par\par\uc2 714 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 November 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The antitrust body's questionable ruling against Singapore's  \uc2 Temasek Holdings\uc2 , its subsidiaries and Telkomsel on Monday just added more evidence of the legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  that has kept most foreign investors away from Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 The Business Competition Supervisory Commission (KPPU) is supposed to play a vital role in a market \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as it is responsible for preventing monopolistic practices and unfair business competition, which were rampant during Soeharto's administration through collusion between big corporations, officials, politicians and Soeharto's cronies and relatives.   \par \par \uc2 The KPPU was greatly welcomed upon its establishment in 2000 as an independent body responsible for enforcing the 1999 law on competition, which serves as the constitution for market mechanisms. A properly functioning KPPU is a strong deterrent keeping big businesses from abusing their market dominance or engaging in other cartel-like practices.   \par \par \uc2 However, an antitrust body that does not possess high standards of technical competence and integrity is not only impotent to defend fair market competition, but could damage the business climate through absurd decisions that create a new legal black hole for investors.   \par \par \uc2 Even more devastating would be if the KPPU could be manipulated by vested interests to harass particular business entities through negative media campaigns or unnecessary investigations.   \par \par \uc2 These are some of the apprehension we felt upon learning of the KPPU's decision Monday and the background events, intrigue, rumors and controversy that preceded the KPPU's investigations into allegations of monopolistic practices by Telkomsel and  \uc2 Indosat\uc2 , the country's largest cellular operators, which together control more than 80 percent of the market.   \par \par \uc2 The legal technicalities and the market and business theories used by the KPPU investigation team in building an antitrust case against  \uc2 Temasek\uc2 , its subsidiaries and Telkomsel are for the legal experts to analyze.   \par \par \uc2 Legal matters, however complex they may be, should make sense, should have a logic. But we find hard it to understand why  \uc2 Temasek\uc2  from the outset was picked on as the primary defendant while the case centered on charges of abuse of market dominance by Telkomsel, the largest cellular operator, and price-fixing by Telkomsel and  \uc2 Indosat\uc2  to keep mobile service prices lucratively high and to bar new players from entering the market.   \par \par \uc2 It should have been the Indonesian government and state-controlled Telkom, which owns 65 percent of Telkomsel, examined as the primary defendants. The Indonesian government also owns 14.29 percent of  \uc2 Indosat\uc2 , while  \uc2 Temasek\uc2  indirectly holds only 35 percent of Telkomsel and almost 31 percent of  \uc2 Indosat.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the government appointed five of the nine members of the board of directors at  \uc2 Indosat\uc2  and most of its commissioners (supervisors). The government also owns a golden share in  \uc2 Indosat\uc2 , which gives it veto power over important corporate decisions. The Telecommunications Regulatory Body also is dominated by government appointees.   \par \par \uc2 So how could  \uc2 Temasek\uc2 , despite its cross-ownership at  \uc2 Indosat\uc2  and Telkomsel, control both companies and fix their prices for the benefit of Telkomsel? This seems entirely illogical because it would be the Indonesian government and not  \uc2 Temasek\uc2  that would benefit the most from Telkomsel's "monopolistic prices".   \par \par \uc2 Temasek\uc2  subsidiary ST Telemedia was one of only two telecommunications companies --  \uc2 Telekom Malaysia\uc2  is the other one -- that submitted final bids in October 2002 for shares of publicly listed  \uc2 Indosat\uc2  put on sale by the government soon after the terrorist bombings in Bali killed hundreds of people.   \par \par \uc2 ST Telemedia paid more than a 50 percent premium over the market price to bag the stake through what was then described by many national and foreign media as a transparent transaction.   \par \par \uc2 The deal also was processed under the political scrutiny of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the stock market watchdog (Bapepam) and the Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM).   \par \par \uc2 But, suddenly five years later,  \uc2 Temasek\uc2  came under an endless wave of smear campaigns, \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion harassment and many other allegations, which was capped with the KPPU investigation and decisions that ordered the Singapore business group to sell its entire stake in either  \uc2 Indosat\uc2  or Telkomsel.   \par \par \uc2 Temasek\uc2  and its subsidiaries will certainly appeal the decisions at the district court and the Supreme Court, but entering the justice system will plunge the  \uc2 Temasek\uc2  group into another legal black hole because of the notorious reputation of Indonesia's courts as one of the most corrupt \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  institutions.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020071120e3bk0000n\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
