\par\par \b \uc2 The debilitating effect of corruption on democracy   \b0\par\par\uc2 Richard L. Armitage , Arlington, VA   \par \uc2 931 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 November 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 I have watched Indonesia's transition to democracy with great optimism. In the nine years since the demise of the Soeharto regime, the people of Indonesia have taken up the banner of democracy and worked for change. They have demonstrated, gone to the polls, and elected officials with the high hope that they would further the country's advances.   \par \par \uc2 Along this path, there have been great successes. One needs only to look to the 2004 elections for signs of progress. But, in any transition, the path is strewn with hurdles. And, in the case of a democratic transition, it is important to understand that elections are not the end of the road.   \par \par \uc2 Democracy requires the institution of basic principles of fairness and openness -- and the rule of law -- to secure good governance and pave the way toward stability and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prosperity. Without that, the future of a country and its people suffer. It is in this regard that I seek to highlight the debilitating effects of corruption for Indonesia's future.   \par \par \uc2 I am asked regularly for my advice on the benefits of doing business in Indonesia. Given the optimism I hold for the country, I am genuinely interested in promoting its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  promise. However, in truth, I am also obliged to note the drawbacks of doing business in a country where corruption is perceived to be commonplace.   \par \par \uc2 There are unhappy facts to disclose. Reports suggest that elements within the government and business community remain entrenched in a way of life that accepts corruption as a cost of doing business. There is poor contract enforcement, inconsistent interpretation or arbitrary enforcement of laws and \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and inefficient enforcement of intellectual property rights. There have been instances of unequal treatment among foreign investors.   \par \par \uc2 Some have been targeted by unfair allegations and been the subject of negative \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion campaigns, most often exploiting nationalism as a means to drive certain foreign investors out of the country. Even \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  bodies meant to enforce correct business practices, such as the Business Competition Supervisory Commission -- the KPPU -- have come under question for their integrity and independence.   \par \par \uc2 For all credible corporations and businesspeople, these facts have a tremendous chilling effect. Large, multinational corporations that otherwise might have approached Indonesian markets with great enthusiasm and resources are considering their options more carefully.   \par \par \uc2 And why wouldn't they when Indonesia is ranked among the lowest third out of 180 countries surveyed for the 2007 Corruption Perception Index prepared by Transparency International, a global anti-corruption civil society organization?   \par \par \uc2 So, predictably, with the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  of doing business in Indonesia have come a dive in investor confidence and a drive to seek opportunities elsewhere. These by-products of corruption are no more clearly seen than in comparisons of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance with other ASEAN members. Whereas foreign direct investment in Indonesia fell by a third last year to US$6 billion from $9 billion the previous year, other countries, such as Vietnam, experienced notable increases. In 2006, foreign direct investment in Vietnam topped $10 billion, the highest since it opened its doors to FDI in 1986.   \par \par \uc2 There are also gaps in development where Indonesia lags behind other ASEAN members.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's unemployment rate remains high at 10.3 percent in 2006, and approximately 42 percent of the Indonesians are living on $1-2 per day. By any measure, those are poor statistics in a region that is experiencing tremendous \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and more particularly for a country that has the intellectual capital, manpower, and natural resources to do better.   \par \par \uc2 Fortunately, there are those in country who are working to improve Indonesia's business environment. President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, most notably, has acknowledged corruption as a major problem and has launched initiatives to reform the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , investment, and labor laws. Although these initiatives have stumbled at times in Parliament, their pursuit and ultimate implementation remain vital.   \par \par \uc2 I have no doubt of President Yudhoyono's conviction to stamp out corruption. He has been consistent in highlighting this effort as one of his top priorities. However, his efforts alone have proven insufficient to secure a level of investor confidence that is necessary to meet Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  potential. It will take a concerted effort by all Indonesians to reject corrupt practices and demand real reform on the government's part.   \par \par \uc2 As in their drive for democratic processes earlier this decade, Indonesians should turn their attention to what now stands as a significant impediment for stability and prosperity -- corruption. There should be tougher approaches to bringing corrupt officials to justice, efforts to end selectivity in investigations and prosecutions, and further civil service reforms to attract capable, responsible people who can understand and enforce the laws. The Indonesian media also should be encouraged to play a more aggressive role in exposing graft.   \par \par \uc2 I raise this as a burning issue not simply for reasons of financial gain on behalf of foreign investors, but because the effects of corruption for Indonesia are real and stand to undermine the tremendous political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  strides Indonesia has made in its transition to democracy. Left unchecked, corruption will cause Indonesia to fall further behind in its ability to support its people and their aspirations -- setting the stage for political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  instability. That would be a terrible tragedy for Indonesia, a country that to date had fostered genuine optimism for its future.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is the President of Armitage International L.C., an international business consultancy. He previously served as U.S. Deputy Secretary of State from 2001 to 2005.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020071122e3bm0000m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
