\par\par \b \uc2 Flexibility key to united ASEAN market, says EU's Barroso   \b0\par\par\uc2 Urip Hudiono , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 486 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 November 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 With its experience of building a common community among diverse nations, the European Union (EU) is calling on other nations not to consider globalization as a threat, but as an opportunity to make further advances and a means of cooperation to resolve global problems.   \par \par \uc2 Europe, in particular, welcomes the latest efforts by the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) to develop a similar multilateral framework, visiting European Commission (EC) President Jose Manuel Durao Barroso said here Friday.   \par \par \uc2 Barroso said that "flexibility and openness" should be at the forefront, and pointed to the EU's experience in uniting 495 million people in 27 countries into a common market as an example that could be emulated by ASEAN, which recently adopted a charter at its recent summit in Singapore, with the aim being to create an ASEAN \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Community by 2010.   \par \par \uc2 As an ASEAN founding member, with the largest population and biggest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the region, Indonesia is well placed to play a leading role in promoting regional integration, and cooperation between the EU and ASEAN, he said.   \par \par \uc2 The EU and ASEAN plan to start negotiations on a free trade agreement next year.   \par \par \uc2 Addressing a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  discussion organized by the Indonesian Council on World Affairs (ICWA), Barroso said that the process of change brought about by globalization was intimidating to many people.   \par \par \uc2 "The sense people have of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the vulnerability they feel about a whole new level of competition, is creating a new politics of anxiety," Barroso said. "Every nation and culture is debating about how to respond and adapt to the challenges of this new world of globalization."   \par \par \uc2 Europe was not immune from such fears, with globalization been seen by some as "Americanization", and the emergence of attempts to use the EU as a wall against globalization.   \par \par \uc2 However, as the trend now was inevitably toward globalization, a proper understanding of the process was needed so as to benefit from it to the maximum.   \par \par \uc2 "Globalization comes from the technological advances in transport and communication, from changing capital and goods markets, and more open economies and societies. No one controls globalization, there is no master behind it. Globalization is the product of the decisions of consumers," Barroso said.   \par \par \uc2 "It is about open society, cheaper goods, more innovation, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  dynamism, poverty reduction, cultural exchanges, and making the opportunity for any individual to keep in touch with the world."   \par \par \uc2 With this understanding of the world becoming more open and intertwined, globalization should thus become the basis for better relations and cooperation among nations in solving the common problems they are facing -- building peace, trade issues, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development, poverty reduction and, most recently, climate change.   \par \par \uc2 "Global problems cannot be solved without global solutions. There is no one planet for Europe, no one planet for Asia. There's only one planet for us to work together on."   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020071124e3bo00001\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
