\par\par \b \uc2 Bali must bring developing nations on board   \b0\par\par\uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati and Robert Zoellick , Jakarta   \par \uc2 742 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 December 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Climate change is a development, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and investment challenge, not just an environmental issue. An effective global accord on climate change will have to recognize the interests and needs of developing countries.   \par \par \uc2 That is why this week in Bali, finance ministers will, for the first time, attend a climate change session in conjunction with the new round of negotiations under the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change. Indonesia, host to the 13th Conference of Parties, is both vulnerable to climate change and a source of large emissions, particularly from deforestation and changes in land use.   \par \par \uc2 After President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono met with the World Bank in September, Indonesia announced it is launching the development of its first low-carbon growth strategy to reduce the carbon intensity of its development path, identify opportunities for climate change mitigation and adaptation, and manage the financing implications of shifting to cleaner carbon development activities.   \par \par \uc2 It is proposing an initiative on reduced emissions from deforestation and degradation, with support from the World Bank and the UK, Australia, Germany and the Netherlands.   \par \par \uc2 Developing countries recognize the dangers climate change poses to their territories, economies and people. They are interested in the potential of carbon markets and new technologies to finance greenhouse gas reductions.   \par \par \uc2 But many are wary of climate change negotiations because of two fears: that international assistance will be diverted from social development and growth plans, and that climate change policies championed by developed countries will constrain the growth of countries moving up behind them.   \par \par \uc2 Unless the concerns of the developing countries are addressed, any new international accord on climate change will be neither global nor successful.   \par \par \uc2 While the environment ministers in Bali will be working on a roadmap to a post-2012 framework, more than three dozen countries are sending finance and development ministers to support this process.   \par \par \uc2 The finance ministers will discuss \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  options, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives and disincentives, and financing arrangements that combine growth and energy sources with low-carbon strategies, technological development, efficiencies and measures to adapt to climate change.   \par \par \uc2 The engagement of finance ministers will help to integrate climate change mitigation and adaptation issues into national priorities and budgets as well as the international dialogue on financing instruments and flows.   \par \par \uc2 Climate change policies cannot just be the frosting on the cake of development; they need to be baked into the recipe of growth and social development.   \par \par \uc2 The World Bank and international financial institutions, working with developed countries, can help. We are devising innovative and concessional financing mechanisms. In Bali, we will launch the Forest Carbon Partnership Facility to help counter deforestation.   \par \par \uc2 The Clean Energy Investment Framework will promote alternative energy, efficiency and lower emissions. For example, Indonesia and the World Bank are co-operating on a geothermal project with support from the Global Environment Facility.   \par \par \uc2 International partners can also assist countries with the implementation and expansion of carbon trading systems to finance low-carbon growth in poorer countries.   \par \par \uc2 The World Bank's private sector arm, the  \uc2 International Finance Corporation\uc2 , can help draw private capital towards developing countries' needs for an estimated US$ 200billion per year of low-carbon energy production.   \par \par \uc2 We also need to encourage research and development in new technologies for low-carbon growth and advance their rapid adoption in the developing world.   \par \par \uc2 For many developing countries, the stresses of climate change are today's crisis, not tomorrow's \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The poorest are the most vulnerable to calamities and adverse changes in health conditions, food production, water resources, coastal integrity and biodiversity.   \par \par \uc2 Yet research and \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on climate adaptation have fallen far behind work on mitigation. We should be developing integrated adaptation and mitigation strategies that will reinforce one another.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia is doing more than hosting the UN conference on climate change. It is also showing developed countries how to engage developing countries in a constructive discussion about the integration of climate change and development strategies.   \par \par \uc2 The Bali meetings need to launch two mutually supportive projects: one is a negotiation to guide a global approach to climate change; and the second is a commitment to support developing countries' efforts to combine development and climate change strategies.   \par \par \uc2 Progress with developing countries will be a prerequisite for a new global climate change agreement that works, and is sustainable environmentally, economically and politically.   \par \par \uc2 The authors are, respectively, the minister of finance for Indonesia and the president of the World Bank.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020071207e3c70000b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
