\par\par \b \uc2 Growth to accelerate despite global slowdow   \b0\par\par\uc2 The Jakarta Post , Jakarta   \par \uc2 585 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 December 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Although many economists are worried that the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown will cast a shadow over the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  next year, Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Boediono says he is confident the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will actually accelerate.   \par \par \uc2 "I've always been optimistic about Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . I believe that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth will be higher than this year," Boediono told reporters Saturday.   \par \par \uc2 He said that the government's target of achieving \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 6.8 percent next year was still feasible, even though many economists estimate that the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown will drag down the pace of growth.   \par \par \uc2 The government's growth target is higher than the 6.4 percent predicted by the World Bank, which says that the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown resulting from high oil prices and the United States' subprime mortgage crisis will also affect Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 The country recorded 6.2 percent growth in the first nine months of 2007. The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has predicted 6.4 percent growth for the fourth quarter of this year, which will bring full-year growth to 6.2 percent, slightly below the government's target of 6.3 percent.   \par \par \uc2 However, a number of senior economists, such as Faisal Basri and Mohamad Ikhsan Mojo, have forecast a gloomier outlook for the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Faisal, for example, said that the increases in fuel prices would further raise production costs for the industrial sector, which has been held back by high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  costs resulting from inefficiency and red tape.   \par \par \uc2 He said that given these circumstances, it would be impossible for the country to achieve the sort of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth targeted by the government.   \par \par \uc2 Boediono said that with higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, the number of people living in poverty would be reduced.   \par \par \uc2 "We're expecting the number to fall by about 15 percent next year," he said.   \par \par \uc2 The World Bank has said that Indonesia has an opportunity in 2008 to reduce the number of people living on under US$2 per day by 4.6 million, from 105.3 million to 100.7 million, out of a total population of 236.4 million.   \par \par \uc2 Boediono said that if the government could stabilize rice prices, it would be able to reduce the poverty rate by more than 15 percent as poor people spend about 30 percent of their incomes on rice.   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, an expert advisor to the minister, Jannes Hutagalung, said the government was currently promoting a number of schemes to improve the investment climate, including the introduction of "one-roof" licensing procedures.   \par \par \uc2 According to the  \uc2 International Finance Corporation\uc2  (IFC), Indonesia ranks 123rd out of 178 countries in the ease-of-doing-business ratings.   \par \par \uc2 "If we could simplify the process for obtaining business licenses, Indonesia's ranking would climb to around the 70 mark," Jannes said.   \par \par \uc2 The government will need to act fast if it wishes Indonesia to continue to be able to compete with its neighbors, such as Thailand and Malaysia, he added.   \par \par \uc2 In September, 