\par\par \b \uc2 Our parliament's immaturity   \b0\par\par\uc2 774 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 December 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 We cannot help but feel more cynicism toward our parliament, which has no sense of urgency in addressing the real issues.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  decision last week to question President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono on the estimated Rp 144.50 trillion (US$16 billion) in emergency liquidity credits \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  granted to financially-distressed banks during the height of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis between November, 1997, and early 1999, is an irresponsible act.   \par \par \uc2 This is the latest evidence of how the childish and trifling politicians of the House often unwisely exercise their constitutional rights. The interpellation motion will simply waste the House's and the government's resources.   \par \par \uc2 We find it flabbergasting to fathom what the House thinks it can achieve by quizzing the President on an issue already settled in August, 2003, with consensus from the House itself.   \par \par \uc2 This move will only overstretch the capacity of the House and the government at a time when both are time-strapped to complete long-delayed reform measures to spur \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, improve the democratic process and create jobs for the millions of unemployed people and alleviate poverty.   \par \par \uc2 It would be more in the interests of the people they represent if House members focused their attention on their important \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  agenda, which includes bills on \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , mining, general elections and the structure and composition of \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  assemblies, all of which have long been behind schedule.   \par \par \uc2 In 2003's final agreement on the emergency credits, which resolved once and for all their four-year dispute, the government reimbursed \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  with 30-year bonds.   \par \par \uc2 The dispute itself arose after an independent audit by the Supreme Audit Agency in 1999 found Rp 138.5 trillion of the loans had not adequately been secured with collateral, and that quite a portion of these funds, supposed to be used to reimburse depositors during the massive bank runs, had been misused by the recipient banks for currency speculation or lending to affiliate businesses.   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  flatly denied any wrongdoing, arguing that, as part of the Cabinet under the authoritarian rule of then president Soeharto, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  ought to obey the president's instruction not to close banks, notably those owned by Soeharto's cronies.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  became a politically independent institution only in May, 1999, immediately after the enactment of a new law on \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Making a political issue out of the emergency liquidity credits now would only create a new source of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially because most of the assets ceded by the owners of the distressed banks -- to repay their debts to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- were sold through the then Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency to domestic and foreign investors.   \par \par \uc2 Around 20 of an estimated 40 large debtors (former bank shareholders) signed closing agreements with the government to resolve once and for all their debts to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 . These closing agreements were concluded after government and independent audits ascertained the value of the assets pledged by the debtors was sufficient and the legal status of the assets was clear.   \par \par \uc2 What is needed now is not political inquiry but vigorous investigation into the auditors' findings on alleged misappropriation and misuse of the liquidity credits.   \par \par \uc2 The House should pressure the government to push harder in investigating and prosecuting the former bank owners and directors who have not yet resolved their debts or were found guilty of misusing the credits.   \par \par \uc2 To our knowledge, the Supreme Audit Agency submitted as early as 2000 to the Attorney General's Office the names of more than 50 Bank Indonesian officials and dozens of former bank owners implicated in the credit misappropriation and misuse findings. But so far, only three of the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's deputy governors have been jailed. Several former bank directors and owners found responsible for misusing credits have also been brought to justice but most of these defendants were either tried in absentia or fled the country before serving their sentences.   \par \par \uc2 The government threatened as early as 2000 to prosecute debtors who were not cooperative and did not show good faith in repaying the emergency liquidity credits, but \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  prosecutors still miserably failed to produce solid legal evidence to prove debtors had truly defaulted on their commitments.   \par \par \uc2 Summoning the President, Cabinet ministers, former ministers and former \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  governors and deputy governors to explain the circumstances and procedures for the extension of the liquidity credits will only waste House and government resources.   \par \par \uc2 The series of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  hearings the House will conduct under the right of inquiry will become largely a meaningless political circus amid a weakening \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as skyrocketing oil prices add \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020071211e3cb0000f\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Stock Exchange Corrected on the Fed's Decision   \b0\par\par\uc2 381 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 December 2007\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The Composite Stock Price Index (IHSG) on the Indonesia Stock Exchange (BEI) was corrected following the US Federal \b \highlight22\uc2 Reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 ' decision to cut its rate yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 The Federal Reserve's decision to cut its rate by 25 basis points to 4.25% is seen as a signal for the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown.   \par \par \uc2 Therefore, capital market players sold their stocks to realize their gains following the index rally over the past few days.   \par \par \uc2 "Investors sold on news and realized their gains after their expectations fulfilled. Besides, the index has already increased too high and the prices of stocks on the domestic bourse have been pricey," said Head of Research at Paramitra Alfa Sekuritas Pardomuan Sihombing yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 The index yesterday was closed at 2,795.84, down by 0.54% or 15.12 points from the record 2,810.96.   \par \par \uc2 Banking stocks, such as Bank Central Asia,  \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2 , and Bank Danamon made the largest contribution to the declining index. Compared to other bourses in Asia Pacific, IHSG had the smallest drop. The Hang Seng index yesterday fell by 2.41%, the Nikkei 225 index by 0.70% and the Straits Times by 1.11%.   \par \par \uc2 Director of  \uc2 Bank Rakyat Indonesia\uc2  (BRI) Sulaiman A. Ariyanto viewed the Fed rate cut would benefit Indonesia's capital market. "The one enjoying the rate cut is the cap