\par\par \b \uc2 Investment outlook in Year of Rat: Fortune or disaster?   \b0\par\par\uc2 Aldo Perkasa , Analyst   \par \uc2 827 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 December 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 A new year brings with it fresh hopes. The "fire pig" of 2007 will soon be exiting, and the "earth rat" of 2008 is coming. What changes will it bring? Fortune or disaster? Will it make or break us?   \par \par \uc2 In the Chinese horoscope, the Year of the Rat is signified by earth and water. In the cycle of birth and destruction, earth is the conqueror of water. So, as the earth is placed on top of the water, it symbolizes control.   \par \par \uc2 However, the water element in the Year of the Rat is strong, so that the earth floats with no foundation. This is a sign of possible tension and confrontation. Hence, a stable and calm atmosphere, with occasional periods of volatility, dominate in the Year of the Rat.   \par \par \uc2 The 2007 "Year of the Fire Pig" has, in some ways, been good, but in other ways bad. Excess liquidity and unbridled optimism from the strong "fire element" of the "fire pig" brought about a lot of speculation in the financial markets. This resulted in a bullish market. At its peak, the Indonesian equity market was up an amazing 50 percent from its level at the beginning of the year and the spread on Indonesian bonds to U.S. treasuries stood at a record low of 140 bps. However, "the fire" then became too hot to handle, as marked by the emergence of the sub-prime mortgage crisis in the United States.   \par \par \uc2 The sub-prime crisis had far reaching implications, leading to a so-called credit crunch, risk-averse behavior and a flight to quality. These factors were behind August's deep correction. In spite of that, the "fire element" continued to dominate, driving speculators and traders to take positions in the market, thus giving stocks the necessary impetus to rebound.   \par \par \uc2 Approaching the end of the year, the "fire element" is starting to weaken. Market sentiment is less bullish now than it was in the first half of 2007. This is because investors have some fears over a possible U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown and higher inflationary pressures given soaring oil prices and the lingering impact of the sub-prime crisis.   \par \par \uc2 Nonetheless, it is not the time to look back but rather to look to the future. In the new year there will be a change in elements and new hopes shall emerge. This leads to the question: "Will the "Year of the Rat" end the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and bring fortune to investors?"   \par \par \uc2 The financial markets and \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will see more stability in the year of the "earth rat" than in the year of the "fire pig". Speculative activities on the markets will decline, and there will be some slowdown in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 This is already evident in China, where inflation is at a 5-year high. That country's policymakers have stated that they will start to pursue tighter monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  - indicating higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a stronger Chinese currency.   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is also expected to slow down in the wake of the sub-prime crisis -- as are the European economies. As a result, contagion could plausibly spread to emerging markets, including Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 Yet, looking back, the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  saw a strong recovery in 2007. The drivers of growth included the agricultural, manufacturing and trade sectors (accounting for about 57 percent of the total growth). And in third quarter, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth rate reached a very respectable 6.5 percent year-on-year, its fastest pace since the financial crisis back in 1998.   \par \par \uc2 On entering 2008, Indonesia should remain on its growth trajectory despite tougher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  challenges. The main risks center on high oil prices and a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown. As a result of high oil prices, the national \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to increase to 1.8 percent of GDP in 2008 (compared with 1.3 percent of GDP this year), while the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown will hit Indonesia's exports.   \par \par \uc2 The fire will lose its strength as the cold of the water changes the atmosphere. So what will be the best strategy to fight off this cold? Should we still be aggressive in our decision making or be more cautious? Well, given that the outlook for this year is not quite so rosy, a defensive and conservative strategy might be the best approach.   \par \par \uc2 However, this does not mean that the Indonesian market will see major declines. After all, local investors are now playing a more active role in the market. Moreover, the Indonesian market is still attractively valued compared to its peers.   \par \par \uc2 This will attract investors looking for higher returns. And as soon as improvements are seen, with the elements starting to show good harmony, then we believe that the market will turn bullish. All in all, then, the "Year of the Rat" may not prove to be too bad after all.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is a portfolio analyst at  \uc2 PT Danareksa Sekuritas\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020071213e3cd00014\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
