\par\par \b \uc2 Greeting neighbors   \b0\par\par\uc2 Christmas is here again! In recent years, many Indonesian Muslims have had mixed feelings around Christmastime about their Christian neighbors who have a different religion. The issue is simple, but it can be troubling if both sides do not realize it: hospitality to others.   \par \uc2 673 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 December 2007\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Of course, a more serious problem is security threats during Christmas, especially after terrorists attacked churches in Jakarta, West Java, East Java, Batam, Riau, and North Sumatra on Christmas eve in 2000.   \par \par \uc2 The threat haunts not only those who celebrate Christmas but also Muslims, because in nearly all terror attacks in Indonesia, the perpetrators have claimed to commit their acts in the name of Islam.   \par \par \uc2 This challenging inter-religious relationship is again evident when some Muslims feel \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  whether they should greet their Christian neighbors on holidays. The Indonesian Ulemas Council (MUI) declared in 1981 that greeting Christians on Christmas was haram (forbidden). According to the MUI, such greetings implied that Muslims recognized Jesus as God, while in Islam Isa (Jesus) is a prophet.   \par \par \uc2 Muslims who ignore the edict argue that a Christmas greeting is only a social courtesy and has nothing to do with their religious faith. They have for generations sent food to neighbors, including non-Muslims, on Idul Fitri or Idul Adha.   \par \par \uc2 But perhaps the problem here is not just the edict, but also growing distrust among different communities, and a failure on the part of the state to protect citizens.   \par \par \uc2 These are just examples of the obstacles facing inter-religious relations in this country. Many Christians feel like victims of a majority dictatorship, while many Muslims have the feeling they are a majority in number but a minority in terms of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  power.   \par \par \uc2 According to the latter perception, the minority control the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and do not want to share their wealth with the poor, most of whom are Muslims. Fear of Christianization among Muslims also remains strong, as is apparent in the controversial \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  that restricts construction of churches.   \par \par \uc2 The presence of "hard-line" Christians has exacerbated the problem. They have little respect for their Muslim neighbors and deem those who do not worship Jesus as Lord to be non-believers who will automatically go to hell.   \par \par \uc2 At a time when Indonesia has emerged as the world's third-largest democracy after India and United States, there is concern that the spirit of diversity, tolerance and inclusiveness is on the decline. This fearful segregation is also creeping into ethnic, social and political relations.   \par \par \uc2 The prospects for a melting pot called Indonesia look gloomy if we buy into the thinking of hard-line groups, which are actually the minority. They are small in quantity but their activities are so noisy that they are perceived as representing the mainstream.   \par \par \uc2 The state often hesitates to tackle religious-related problems and prefers to hide them under the carpet. Hundreds of churches throughout the country have reportedly been closed by force. Ahmadiyah followers now face great difficulties after many of their mosques or shelters were attacked by people who brand them heretical.   \par \par \uc2 Our nation is perhaps sick and lacking in self confidence, especially since the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis that hit the country in 1997. The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still ailing, and millions of people are jobless. It is the duty of the whole nation, not just the government, to bring the country out of crisis and revive its hopes for a better future.   \par \par \uc2 The nation was built on pluralism, not only in terms of religion, but also ethnicity, language and region, not to mention opinion. One thing is certain: Most Indonesians are religious, and they are moderate, because they have been accustomed to dealing with differences since they were born. That's why the country's founding fathers formulated a constitution that upholds and protects pluralism. The nation of Indonesia will no longer exist if pluralism withers.   \par \par \uc2 In the spirit of pluralism, Christmas therefore provides a golden moment to us all to reinvigorate the commitment to working with other communities to build a respectable, peaceful and prosperous nation. Merry Christmas!   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020071224e3co0000n\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Investment Ratio Stagnant   \b0\par\par\uc2 426 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 December 2007\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2007 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Indonesia's investment-to-GDP ratio until September 2007 hit 24.1% or IDR698.9 trillion, up from 24% in the same period last year.   \par \par \uc2 Researcher at the Center of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Research at the National Institute of Sciences (LIPI) Maxensius Tri Sambodo revealed the figure showed investment climate in Indonesia had not changed much, making investors reluctant to spend money into the real sector.   \par \par \uc2 "It is true this year we have already had a good Investment Law that applies level playing field to foreign and domestic investors. However, the small investment ratio shows there are still investment barriers at home," he informed Bisnis yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 Some of the barriers, he continued, were lack of legal certainty and regional regulations that created high-cost \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The sluggish investment ratio was also caused by the decline of government capital \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Record by Bisnis showed the government this year lowered its \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  by IDR11.2 trillion from IDR763.6 trillion in the 2007 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to IDR752.4 trillion in the 2007 Revised State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Yet recovered   \par \par \uc2 According to Maxensius, the ideal investment ratio should be around 30% or the same like that before the 1997 crisis. "If the investment ratio can return to the level before crisis, we can say that the investment situation in Indonesia has recovered."   \par \par \uc2 The Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) exposed the realization of domestic investment licenses until December 15 reached IDR125.94 trillion or the record high before the crisis.   \par \par \uc2 On the other hand, the Central Bureau for Statistics (BPS) recorded the cumulative gross fixed capital growth until the third quarter of 2007 only reached 7.9% with IDR700.7 trillion in total investments. To reach an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 6.3%, the cumulative gross fixed capital growth should increase by 12%.   \par \par \uc2 Director of Macro Planning at the National Development Planning Agency (Bappenas) Bambang Prijambodo disclosed the sluggish investment ratio happened amidst external \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  risks, such as the soaring international oil price, the subprime mortgage crisis and the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown.   \par \par \uc2 "The three risks have curbed the world's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, making it grow by less than 3%."   \par \par \uc2 In the meantime, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team of the Prosperous Justice Party (PKS) spokesperson Rama Pratama viewed the real sector growth was still being curbed by fluctuating \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  power, lack of government's clear real sector-related programs, and lack of loans disbursed by banks.   \par \par \uc2 He argued that government regulations had to serve as \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the real sector. "However, regulations issued are often overlapping, creating \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  investment climate," he said. (Bisnis/bsi/ags)   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020071224e3co0002v\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
