\par\par \b \uc2 The year ahead:  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  prospects for Indonesia   \b0\par\par\uc2 James Castle , Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,348 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 January 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 25\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 After a decade of domination by domestic concerns, the major \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  for 2008 comes from abroad in the form of potential collateral damage from America's sub-prime mortgage crisis. Although the crisis is centered in the U.S, it is reverberating through all of the world's major financial centers.   \par \par \uc2 Prospects for the economies of the U.S. and Europe are at their weakest in several years. The OECD's December report cuts its 2008 U.S growth forecast to 2.0 percent and Europe's to 1.9 percent. These are significantly lower than OECD's May forecasts of 2.5 percent and 2.6 percent respectively.   \par \par \uc2 While these growth levels hardly constitute a crisis, many other forecasts are even more gloomy. But even if the OECD's forecasts prove optimistic and the U.S. slides into recession in a worst case scenario, developing Asia has little direct exposure to the crisis and Indonesia has almost none so the effect here should be marginal.   \par \par \uc2 Indeed, whatever difficulties a weaker global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  may bring, Indonesia enters 2008 having recorded its highest growth rate in a decade. For the first time since 1996, the country's gross domestic product (GDP) growth last year would most likely exceed 6 percent, providing a solid base for even higher growth in 2008.   \par \par \uc2 In fact, the major clouds on Indonesia's 2008 horizon come not from recession in the U.S. Rather, they come from the impact of high oil prices on the government's unsustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  bill and the inflationary pressures that are pushing up domestic prices, endangering the recovery of consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  that is driving growth and harming the poor.   \par \par \uc2 In this regard, a slowdown in global growth may actually prove beneficial here as the global rise in oil prices will at least slow and probably reverse. While an overall commodity price contraction will hurt the nominal value of some of Indonesia's exports, it would be a net positive for the country as it would also reduce inflationary pressures on domestic manufacturers where margin squeezes are forcing prices up and reducing consumer buying power. In any case, Indonesia can do little about global oil prices, so it must find other ways to combat inflation.   \par \par \uc2 A major factor in the inflation threat here comes from the failure of the Indonesian rupiah to follow most regional currencies that are appreciating against the U.S dollar. Here, government and \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's policies have a great deal of influence.   \par \par \uc2 At first glance, it seems strange that the rupiah has not strengthened along with the baht, peso, rupee and Singapore dollar since Indonesia's foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 , now over US$54 billion, are rising steadily, exports are up 13 percent so far last year and import growth was even stronger (up 17 percent through the third quarter), indicating greater investment. Despite this strength, the rupiah has actually depreciated over 3 percent against the fading U.S. dollar last year while the baht, peso, rupee and Singapore dollar had an average appreciation of over 10 percent.   \par \par \uc2 So why has the rupiah lagged its regional neighbors? The reasons for its failure to appreciate are two-fold.   \par \par \uc2 Firstly, there is great concern about the impact of the rising oil prices on the national \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to the large fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Investors are worried both about the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  response.   \par \par \uc2 There is concern that the government's unwillingness to raise fuel prices will increase the annual \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  above 2 percent and drain funds away from more important infrastructure and other social development plans. Most agree that another major fuel price hike like 2005 will harm consumers too much and damage the administration's re-election prospects.   \par \par \uc2 Still if oil prices stay at or above $95 per barrel, adjustments will have to be made. Restricted availability of subsidized gasoline in major urban areas is one likely tactic that could provide some short term relief. Ultimately, the country needs a series of mild, steady price increase, perhaps along the lines of the indexing scheme that was imprudently abandoned by the previous administration in 2003 and unwisely rejected by the current government in October 2005.   \par \par \uc2 Equally important, the market also sees Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  as being too low. With inflation running at 6.7 percent, the latest reduction in \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's (BI) benchmark rates from 8.25 to 8 percent has narrowed the spread between \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and inflation, making short term yields unattractive. The current spread of only 130 basis points is below the spread of 200-250 basis points that the market would prefer.   \par \par \uc2 While Indonesian yields remain high, the low interest rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is the main factor preventing an appreciation of the rupiah and keeping inflation high. Rupiah attractiveness is further reduced because the market fears that BI will remain too aggressive in its interest cuts because it tried to achieve its stated interest rate target of 5-7 percent last year and 4-6 percent in 2008.   \par \par \uc2 In defense of lower rates, one can argue that the U.S Federal Reserve will continue to lower rates and that oil prices will retreat further by mid-2008, taking some pressure off the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . These arguments are likely to be true, but acting ahead of the fact is a gamble.   \par \par \uc2 Central bankers, however, should not be gamblers and in the current \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  environment caution is in order. The consumer and the real sector in Indonesia are much more sensitive to currency rates and inflation than \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It would be more prudent for the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to signal a moratorium on further interest rate decreases and even start to prepare the market for possible increases if inflation stays above six per cent. This would be the focus back on reducing inflation and protecting the poor.   \par \par \uc2 Aside from inflation, other broad \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  trends are favorable. Trade remains robust as noted above and the merchandise trade surplus at over $20 billion is very solid and can easily withstand short term commodity price declines. Real sector growth continues to improve. Investment is slowly moving upward and should exceed 25 percent of GDP last year, according to the World Bank.   \par \par \uc2 While well below an optimal level of 30 percent of GDP, this is a significant improvement. As recently as 2003, the ratio was below 20 percent. The government also has plans to increase transportation and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  works \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  by Rp 16.6 trillion or 48 percent this year. If realized, this will provide a tremendous boost to the country's ailing infrastructure.   \par \par \uc2 Cement consumption, another key real time indicator of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity, was up over seven per cent through October, a significant improvement over 2006. October consumer sentiment as measured by Danareksa showed its first increase since July and their quarterly Business Sentiment Index that had been flat at around 115 for over a year, moved up to 120 last March and was at 135 in September. All this bodes extremely well for strong growth this year.   \par \par \uc2 Such bullish business sentiment is confirmed by the fact that investment approval figures from the Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) for the first six months of last year ($29 billion) actually exceeded the total in 2006 ($28 billion).   \par \par \uc2 The keys to higher growth in 2008 are reining in inflation, managing the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  well in the face of significant fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  increases and pushing through as much of the budgeted increase in infrastructure \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  as possible. Success in these areas will reinforce business and consumer sentiment and attract more private investment in both the financial markets and the real sector.   \par \par \uc2 As a result, despite an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  global environment, investment should be up significantly this year. Consumer buying power should hold up. Job creation should increase and overall GDP growth is very likely to meet if not exceed the government's target of 6.8 percent.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is the founder of CastleAsia, past president of the American Chamber of Commerce and founding Chairman of the International Business Chamber in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080103e4130001l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
