\par\par \b \uc2 Indonesia's  \highlight22\uc2 fiscal \highlight\uc2  challenges for 2008   \b0\par\par\uc2 Taimur Baig , Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,220 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 January 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 26\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  steps into 2008 with strong momentum. Buoyed by supportive policies, a largely favorable export environment, and strong consumption and investment sentiment, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has accelerated in the first three quarters of 2007, and was on track to expand by over 6 percent for last year.   \par \par \uc2 This would be an outcome of note, as it would mark the fastest growth rate seen in this decade. Indonesia appears to be emerging from the shadow of the financial crisis of the late 1990s and displaying considerable intrinsic strength.   \par \par \uc2 The critical question for Indonesia is whether the growth momentum will be maintained in 2008 in the face of several external risks.   \par \par \uc2 First, as developed economies slow down (primarily due to housing-led difficulties), export performance will likely weaken in 2008.   \par \par \uc2 Second, if world oil prices remain high, \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be constrained as \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  demand soars, and if the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  burden becomes onerous, and oil prices are passed through, inflation may rise.   \par \par \uc2 Third, the exchange rate could come under pressure if investors become weary of their exposure to Indonesia as inflation rises and export oriented businesses are impacted by waning external demand.   \par \par \uc2 For growth to be sustained in 2008, domestic demand has to compensate for a likely slowdown in exports. We see a number of signs that this could indeed be the case.   \par \par \uc2 First, private consumption should remain strong in the midst of strong consumer sentiment and favorable employment conditions.   \par \par \uc2 Second, the government's ambitious \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  program in 2008 -- especially in the areas of development and capital \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- should provide strong impetus through rising \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consumption and job creation.   \par \par \uc2 Third, strong domestic and external interest in investing in Indonesia's resource \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  should persist, especially as liquidity conditions are likely to remain favorable.   \par \par \uc2 The prevailing strength in employment and income conditions has boosted consumer confidence. Since dipping sharply in 2005 when inflation spiked due to a substantial domestic oil price adjustment, surveys have reported a steady increase in confidence on the perception of overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions. \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's consumer confidence survey reported its highest reading in a year in November. We expect the reading to remain high in the coming months, underpinning consumption and business activities.   \par \par \uc2 Business activities are on an upswing. According to the survey of business activities, broad based improvement has been continuing since late 2006 in the growth critical areas of agriculture, mining, financial services, and manufacturing. Momentum in these types of activities should persist short of a major \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  shock.   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  has made significant progress in recent years with respect to monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  implementation, including the adoption of an inflation target framework in 2005. Since then, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's track record has been mostly positive, especially in late 2005 and 2006 when the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest rate had to be kept at a high level as inflation spiked. How the bank tackles inflation in 2008 will be a significant test, given the various challenges ahead.   \par \par \uc2 First and foremost among these challenges is to control inflation expectations at a period when domestic demand is very strong. Inflation bottomed out in the middle of 2007 and has since risen appreciably. While a sharp resurgence in food price inflation has been the most striking factor in inflation picking up since then, strong demand has been pushing up most prices, leading to a generalized trend increase in core prices. Indeed, core inflation has continued to rise unabated since June.   \par \par \uc2 Fueling additional actual and expected inflation has been a sustained rise in world oil prices. Being a large importer of refined oil products, Indonesia spends a substantial amount of resources (both in terms of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  and administration) by keeping fuel prices controlled in most parts of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . If world oil prices remain high, there could well be a point when the authorities are forced to pass on some of the prices, which may then lead to a jump in inflation.   \par \par \uc2 Our analysis, drawing on the experience from the 2005 price hike, suggests that a 10 percent increase in domestic fuel prices can add as much as 2.5 percent to headline inflation. As 2008 progresses, movements in world oil prices will remain the principal driver of inflation expectations in Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  is on record that it is comfortable with real \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  between 1 percent and 2 percent. Real rates are toward the bottom of the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's comfort zone (after the December rate cut), while growth has accelerated. Any further decline in the real rate could exacerbate inflationary impulses. We don't expect BI to cut its \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate any further.   \par \par \uc2 We expect broad based inflation pressure to persist in 2008. Hence our baseline inflation forecast is 6.5 percent, i.e. we expect the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's inflation target of 4-6 percent to be breached. We also consider that the risks to the inflation outcome are skewed to the upside.   \par \par \uc2 Oil prices and strong domestic demand could push up prices further during the course of the year. Some downside risks to inflation could materialize too, if the exchange rate appreciates, if productive investments made recently begin to help capacity, and if the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  slows down in response to a sharper slowdown in global growth.   \par \par \uc2 Lately, as world oil prices have surged, the focus of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has shifted from much needed priority \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  to financing the increase in energy \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook for 2008 is subject to some \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to surging oil prices.   \par \par \uc2 A presentation by the concerned ministries in late-November revealed the seriousness with which the government is examining the potential impact of oil prices on the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  position. We found the multiple scenario analysis of the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  risks and mitigating measures presented by the authorities informative and transparent.   \par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, our projection for 2008 is for the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to be somewhat worse than the 1.7 percent of GDP expected by the authorities. Given the very large increase in expenditures planned for the year (e.g. social plus capital \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  are programmed to rise by 42 percent), we are sure that there will be room available for savings on the \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  side, but given the run-up to the 2009 election, the scope for that may be limited.   \par \par \uc2 Our baseline forecast for the 2008 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  outcome, built on our in-house average oil price projection of around US$75 and the above discussed factors, is for the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to rise to 2 percent of GDP. If oil prices jump to $100 and full \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  are maintained along with some mitigating measures, the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  would worsen by another half percentage point of GDP. A partial pass-through could reduce the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but that would be accompanied by increased inflation and possibly a slowdown in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities.   \par \par \uc2 All in all, in 2008, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  makers will find themselves balancing rising domestic demand impulse against strong price pressure and waning external demand.   \par \par \uc2 We see the authorities as capable of performing this balancing act, through careful monitoring and \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  action, if necessary, to ensure that inflation does not accelerate in the face of strong domestic demand, or the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  position is not undermined by rising \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  demands.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is a Director at Global Markets Research,  \uc2 Deutsche Bank.\uc2  This is a personal view.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080103e4130001p\p