\par\par \b \uc2 Faulty  \highlight22\uc2 central bank policy \highlight\uc2  may upset  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 Christopher Lingle , Bangkok   \par \uc2 1,258 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 January 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 27\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Forecasting the course of an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has a lot in common with supernatural methods that pretend to offer a window into the future. When tealeaves are read, an eye is cast at what appeared in the past in order to divine unseen events.   \par \par \uc2 Similarly, existing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data are used as an indicator of what should follow based upon a number of subjective assumptions and interpretations. Given this subjectivity, techniques of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data analysis tend to be as arcane and unreliable as methods of fortune telling. And so there should be doubt about what economists predict.   \par \par \uc2 Of course, there is better accuracy in events that unfold in the near future. For example, the consensus forecasts for the full-year growth rate for 2007 of Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 6.2 percent, the fastest since 1996 when the rate was 7.8 percent may be on target.   \par \par \uc2 But forecasting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions at greater remove from the present involves much greater risks just as it does in weather forecasting. That means that greater \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be attached to the forecast for the rate of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2008 by the Indonesian government that is in the range of 6.4 to 6.7 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Since conjuring up an overall outlook of Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for 2008 cannot be done in isolation, it turns out that this might be wishful thinking. A forecast by Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development suggests that 2008 will herald slower growth for the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the lowest rate in five years.   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Indonesia \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be influenced by knock-on effects of the sub-prime mortgage turmoil in the U.S. and higher international commodity prices. Indonesia produces the most oil and gas in Southeast Asia but is faces the pain of being a net oil importer with prices far above the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumption of $60 per barrel.   \par \par \uc2 Of course, there are bright spots given the strong global demand for key commodity exports like coal, palm oil, and rubber along with a mild resurgence of tourist arrivals. And as the biggest exporter of coal for power plants, rising prices could boost Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth over the coming year.   \par \par \uc2 The outlook on Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for 2008 offered here will dwell less on past data that on the effects of current \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on quantitative and qualitative growth prospects.   \par \par \uc2 Unfortunately, the good news for the local \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been undermined by step taken by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI). A cut in the benchmark BI rate to 8 percent in recent weeks, the 14th since May 2006 for a total decline of 4.75 percentage points, it is the lowest rate since being introduced in 2005.   \par \par \uc2 Following \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  orthodoxy, BI justified the latest rate cut on reported easing of upward pressure on prices. Apparently, the consumer price index (CPI) rose 0.18 percent in November over October, up 6.71 percent from a year earlier. This put it at the lower end of forecasts. The year-to-year core CPI measure that removed the effect of food and energy prices was up in November to 6.25 percent, up from 5.66 percent in August.   \par \par \uc2 Given that the CPI was 12 percent in late 2005, many commentators give high marks for the recent inflation-to-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 -growth track record. Such praise is misplaced because \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has done immense harm to long-term \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth prospects.   \par \par \uc2 In the first instance, the current rate of price increases would cause the price level to more than double in less than 10 years. But the actual effect of higher prices for the man on the street is likely to be much higher and come much more quickly. This is because of the tendency for government officials to underreport inflation estimates.   \par \par \uc2 Since CPI reveals rising prices that are fundamentally caused by expansionary monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , there is a tendency to underestimate these numbers. As such, central bankers and finance ministries have an incentive to underreport inflation, they also tend to obscure the true cause of inflation, pumping up the money supply.   \par \par \uc2 For example, blame for inflation is often diverted to supply disruptions or higher demand for goods. The current scapegoat is higher oil prices or the ravenous appetite of the Chinese \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  machine that is devouring prodigious amounts of commodities.   \par \par \uc2 But demand alone cannot push up the general level of prices unless there is loose monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to pump in more credit or freshly-printed money. If the money supply remained under tighter control, the increase in some prices would require an offsetting decline in other prices. And so it is that the blame for the damage from overall increases in the general trend of prices lies squarely with those in charge of monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 It is important to note that the harm from a general rise in prices hits only some groups of people while others will be unaffected and others reaping benefits. This is because all prices will not rise at the same rate. As such, inflation always has a bigger impact on the production and consumption of some goods more than others.   \par \par \uc2 It turns out that loose monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  tends to redistribute income and wealth from the poor to the rich and from the weak to the strong. In particulars, it causes a decline in the real incomes of pensioners and low-income earners that consume most of their income.   \par \par \uc2 Such \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  injustice is bad enough. But rising price levels cause widespread damage to the overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by encouraging speculative buying and resource misallocation.   \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  operates under a mistaken belief that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth can be fine-tuned or conjured up by fiddling with \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The so-called BI rate operates as a reference for bank rates and bill sales.   \par \par \uc2 In lowering the BI rate, it is hoped that banks will lower their rates and lend more to households and businesses so that higher consumption and investment can boost growth. But lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut two ways. As commercial banks lower deposit rates, some saving is discouraged so there will be a lower stock of real savings from long-term income needed for sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.   \par \par \uc2 It is also thought that lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  bring greater optimism that acts as a \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the real sector of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . While this is a common belief among mainstream economists, it is pie-in-the-sky nonsense.   \par \par \uc2 Consumers or business leaders may be tricked into being more confident through false signals created by increased government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  or artificially-low \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But new borrowing or investment inspired by artificial and temporary stimuli that will dry up or be reversed leads to unfulfilled future expectations.   \par \par \uc2 This reversal and drying up of \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -induced \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  is inevitable since it eventually leads to rising consumer prices. And then liquidations of ill-advised investments must occur that pushes up unemployment and slows down the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Happily, there are better \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  approaches to set the stage for higher sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. In particular, the Indonesian government can improve the overall business environment to inspire restructuring, increase productivity and reduce restrictions on commerce. Such steps are the best way to soften the unavoidable pain of restructuring and liquidations set into motion by ill-advised monetary and credit \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  .   \par \par \uc2 The writer is Research Scholar at the Centre for Civil Society in New Delhi and Professor of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  at Universidad Francisco Marroquin in Guatemala. He can be reached at Clingle@ufm.edu.gt.   \par \par \u