\par\par \b \uc2 RI floats bonds in tight mart   \b0\par\par\uc2 690 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 January 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's US$2 billion bond flotation in New York last Friday showed several encouraging developments despite great concerns over the weakening global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the financial market amid the lingering impact of the sub-prime mortgage loan crisis in the United States last August.   \par \par \uc2 The fact that the dollar bond issue was more than 50 percent oversubscribed indicates that despite the international credit crunch funds are plentiful but at the right price. The government sold $1 billion of 10-year bonds to yield 6.95 percent or 298.6 basis points higher than U.S. Treasuries and $1 billion of 30-year securities to yield 7.75 percent or 329.10 basis points than U.S. government debts.   \par \par \uc2 True, these yields are higher than the 6.75 percent offered by Indonesia's 30-year $1.5 billion bonds issued in February 2007. But given the difficult global financial condition caused by the U.S. sub-prime mortgage loan crisis, the 6.95 and 7.75 percent yields seemed to be the best the Indonesian government could get today.   \par \par \uc2 Some analysts have attacked the government bond deal as too expensive, putting a heavy burden on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . They said the yields the government will pay are much higher than those imposed on dollar bonds issued by the Philippines, Thailand and Malaysia but the comparison was not relevant because the latter were all issued last year. The Indonesian dollar bonds were the first issued in New York this year by a Southeast Asian country. A better comparison would be the recent bonds issued by the Venezuelan government, which yielded 8.8 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Moreover, the latest survey by Standard&Poor's and Fitch Ratings rated Indonesian sovereign debts as BB-, which is three levels below the investment grade, while  \uc2 Moody's\uc2  gave a Ba3 rating.   \par \par \uc2 Yet more encouraging is the fact that American investors bought 47 percent of the 10-year bonds and 52 percent of the 30-year bonds with the other 38 percent taken up by European investors and the remainder by Asian investors. This is more evidence of the stronger confidence of global investors in Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is projected to expand by at least 6.5 percent this year, up from 6.3 percent last year.   \par \par \uc2 The successful dollar bond issuance will help improve market confidence in other debt instruments, notably rupiah bonds, the government will issue during the current \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. The government plans to issue Rp 91.6 trillion (US$9.7 billion) worth of rupiah and dollar bonds this year to plug its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  hole.   \par \par \uc2 The steady decline in both international, notably the U.S., and domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the strong appetite of global investors in seeking higher returns in emerging markets with reasonable risks seems also to have contributed to the strong market reception of Indonesian global bonds.   \par \par \uc2 However, maintaining market confidence is a tremendous challenge, especially amid the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about international oil prices and the rise in food prices that have caused strong inflationary pressures. The government therefore should not let this heightened market confidence go to its head, let alone feel complacent that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  landscape ahead will all be smooth.   \par \par \uc2 How the government maintains its prudent \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  management and implements more concerted efforts to bolster exports and investment to offset the impact of the weakening global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will determine the government's sovereign risks, which in turn will influence the costs of its borrowing.   \par \par \uc2 Even though buying Indonesia's bonds with maturities ranging from 10 to 30 years means investing in the long-term outlook of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the great market reception of the bond issue cannot yet be seen entirely as the restoration of international investor confidence in the country.   \par \par \uc2 Bonds, though classified as a long-term investment, are only a portfolio investment that can easily be dumped on the market at the first sign of trouble. Foreign direct investment is a better gauge of investor confidence because this kind of capital is ploughed into fixed assets -- to build productive plants that generate employment.   \par \par \uc2 _________   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080117e41h0000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Index to Still Depend on Global Sentiments   \b0\par\par\uc2 449 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 January 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The stock market is estimated to fluctuate in the first quarter of 2008, while the Composite Stock Index Market (IHSG) this week is predicted to highly fluctuate with a possibility of rebound.   \par \par \uc2 Analyst at Bumiputera Capital Indonesia Ridwan Novayanto explained IHSG movement this week would depend on the development in the US bourse, US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data, and regional bourse movements.   \par \par \uc2 Some data on US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , such as early unemployment rate and house sales, are scheduled to be released on Thursday. On domestic level, there is no agenda scheduled to release important \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data.   \par \par \uc2 Therefore, this week the market will lack of data-driven sentiments. Nevertheless, the market will be filled with speculation for the Fed rate cut approaching the Federal Open Market Committee meeting next week.   \par \par \uc2 With recession looming, some market players hope the Fed Rate can be cut by more than 25 basis points from 4.25%.   \par \par \uc2 Furthermore, Ridwan viewed since the market this month would be \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , market players would only determine their course of investments for this year starting from February.   \par \par \uc2 "Market players will tend to wait and see, despite the fact many stocks have been undervalued. They may buy some stocks, but they won't do it aggressively," he said.   \par \par \uc2 He forecasted IHSG this week would be volatile at 2,594-2,700 and recommended investors to collect telecommunication and plantation stocks.   \par \par \uc2 Potential to rebound   \par \par \uc2 Separately, analyst at Optima Securities Ikhsan Binarto argued with the manageable drop in the Dow Jones index by 59 points on Friday, regional bourses had potential to rebound.   \par \par \uc2 "The drop is better than over 300 points before. After pressures to sell are over, Asian and domestic bourses are potential to rebound."   \par \par \uc2 TLKM and ISAT stocks, which made the largest contribution to the index drop last week, are estimated not yet to recover. On the other hand, mining and plantation sectors are still considered attractive.   \par \par \uc2 In the meantime,  \uc2 Citigroup\uc2  views this year the capital markets in the developing countries would be better than those in the developed ones. However,  \uc2 Citigroup\uc2  also take precaution against bubble risk in the emerging markets.   \par \par \uc2 Head of Research at Citi Florence Tan estimated the domestic market would fluctuate in the first quarter of 2008 to later be probably closed at 3,030 at the yearend.   \par \par \uc2 According to her, the pressures of inflation hike and fast money circulation approaching the general election 2009 would narrow a room for the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) to cut its rate this year.   \par \par \uc2 "Strong \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals and bright profit outlook will positively affect the market, but interest rate hike will press down investors' positive sentiments," she explained at  \uc2 Citigroup\uc2  market outlook 2008. (Bisnis/pul)   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020080121e41l0002u\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
