\par\par \b \uc2 Selling bonds in turbulent times   \b0\par\par\uc2 Helmi Arman , Economist   \par \uc2 896 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 January 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 As long as oil prices remain elevated, the government may be better off focusing its bond issuances on domestic investors.   \par \par \uc2 A couple of weeks ago the Finance Ministry issued US$2 billion of dollar-denominated government bonds to help plug this year's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , in a sale that drew criticism from local media given the perceived high yields.   \par \par \uc2 Whether or not the bond was fairly priced will not be discussed here. However, it is important to highlight how the changing dynamics of global financial markets are implicating the financing of this year's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The market today is much different from, say, six months ago. The global credit crunch from the U.S. mortgage market collapse late last year has only started to emerge. Risk aversion and volatility in financial markets have risen.   \par \par \uc2 For example, in the U.S. yields on Treasury securities have generally declined, reflecting expectations of aggressive rate cuts by the Federal Reserve going forward. The yield on the 10-year U.S. Treasury note, which was floating at around 4.7 percent mid-last year, has dropped by more than 1 percentage point to around 3.6 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Unfortunately the lower borrowing costs in the U.S. haven't been followed by lower borrowing costs in Indonesia. As risk aversion rises, credit default swap spreads on emerging market bonds -- which is basically the cost of insuring against default risk -- have been constantly on the rise.   \par \par \uc2 Concurrently the differences in yields between Indonesian government-issued securities and U.S. Treasury securities have been widening.   \par \par \uc2 Volatility too has been exorbitant. Let's consider the six-month rolling standard deviation of weekly returns on the Indonesian government bond maturing in 2017. Back in January 2007, the figure stood at around 0.5 percent. It has persistently risen since June last year and has now doubled to over 1.0 percent.   \par \par \uc2 What are the implications to Indonesia of these changes in market conditions? Firstly, the financing of the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- in terms of both rupiah and dollar bonds -- has become a more complicated task.   \par \par \uc2 Not only will the government have to issue a higher amount of bonds in net terms (i.e. Rp 91.6 trillion vs. Rp 58.5 trillion last year), it also has to do so in times of increased \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Dollar-denominated bond issuances have become a more challenging sell, as the U.S. dollar is set to depreciate amid an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown. It is therefore no wonder the bulk of buyers from the last sovereign bond auction was reportedly U.S.-based, as opposed to Asia-based, investors.   \par \par \uc2 While the dollar is exposed to currency risk, so too is the rupiah. Indeed, rupiah government bonds of various tenors are currently yielding 8-10.5 percent; they do offer relatively attractive increments over bond yields of many developed countries.   \par \par \uc2 However, investors have to weigh this against the currency risk stemming from a shrinking trade surplus.   \par \par \uc2 Trade data reveals the highly anticipated growth in non-oil commodity exports so far hasn't been able to counterbalance the burgeoning import bill.   \par \par \uc2 In November, data from the statistics office showed Indonesia's trade surplus dropping to US$2.3 billion, a three-year low. This at least partially explains the 2 percent depreciation of the rupiah against the dollar during the month.   \par \par \uc2 So without a substantial pull-back in oil prices, currency risk will remain elevated; this in turn may hold back foreign investors' appetite for rupiah-denominated government bonds.   \par \par \uc2 At this point it is unclear whether more dollar issuances are planned. What's clear is that rupiah issuances have only just started and have some way to go.   \par \par \uc2 The need for further diversification of the domestic investor base has been acknowledged by officials. But in spite of that, domestic investors obviously do not have the capacity to absorb all the issuances.   \par \par \uc2 Given this limitation, and the currency volatility holding back foreign investors' appetite, the risk for the government having to give away higher yields in its auctions is quite substantial.   \par \par \uc2 So is it doomsday for the government? Not yet. The tables may turn if oil prices retreat. A substantial pull-back in oil prices would be good for inflation expectations and would also reduce currency risk. This may be able to help boost foreign investors' appetite for rupiah bonds.   \par \par \uc2 The good news is that many, including the government itself judging by its $60-per-barrel oil price assumption in the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , believe oil prices will ease from current levels as global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth decelerates.   \par \par \uc2 Should this be the case, then it could be a good strategy for the government in the meantime to focus on issuances geared to domestic audiences, such as retail bonds (which suits the needs of domestic individual investors) or even zero-coupon bonds and treasury bills (which are sought by banks).   \par \par \uc2 Only after the expected decline in oil prices materializes would it make better sense to go full-throttle on regular fixed-rate issuances.   \par \par \uc2 Indeed, as the past few weeks have demonstrated, timing the market is difficult, if not impossible. But the government needs a clear strategy to avoid being "cornered" by investors.   \par \par \uc2 If policymakers truly believe oil prices will ease, what can be a better option than to act upon it?   \par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist at PT Bahana Securities   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080123e41n0001c\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 The Fed Tries to Tame Market   \b0\par\par\uc2 956 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 January 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The US \b \highlight22\uc2 Central Bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the Federal Reserve, cuts its rate for the first time as an emergency response since 2001 to prevent worse \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. The rate cut to 3.5% is expected to alleviate the global financial market, which once plummeted.   \par \par \uc2 The decision maker at The Fed, The Federal Open Market Committee (FMOC), cuts overnight loan interest rate by 75 basis points to 3.5% from 4.25%. FOMC previously was scheduled to hold its meeting on January 29-30.   \par \par \uc2 "When the tension in the market loosens, the financial has already been damaged widely," said The Fed in its statement in Washington.   \par \par \uc2 In line with The Fed rate cut by 75 basis points, the White House yesterday hinted to provide over US$150 billion \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  packet to prevent the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  from plunging into recession. "I haven't heard from anyone about \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  more than 1%, but that doesn't mean we have shut down door to follow-up negotiations," said White House spokesperson Dana Perino as quoted by Bloomberg yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 Previously, it was reported that President George W. Bush proposed a \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  packet worth US$150 billion or around 1% of GDP. The packet consists of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  discounts for low- and medium-income people and \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  reduction for the business industry. "Bush also has a full faith in the Fed Governor Ben S. Bernanke's measure and predicts there will be no recession in the US. However, there will be indeed \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown," said Perino.   \par \par \uc2 Unfortunately, stock bourses in the US didn't respond optimally to the Washington's measure. The Dow Jones index fell by 144.7 to 11,954.53 at the trade opening in New York.   \par \par \uc2 Before the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was taken, most indices on regional and global levels plummeted yesterday. The Composite Stock Price Index (IHSG) even hit its five-year record low. IHSG yesterday dropped by 7.70% or 191.35 points to 2,294.52. The index even once took a nosedive by 10% or more than 250 points to 2,231.48.   \par \par \uc2 Data by Bloomberg showed the decline of IHSG was the largest since October 2002, when the index plunged after Bali blast that killed 200 people. Since earlier this year, the index has fallen by 436.98 points from 2,731.507 on January 2.   \par \par \uc2 Fundamental still strong   \par \par \uc2 Analyst at Sucorinvest Central Gani Securities Albert Panjaitan estimated the index drop was more caused by negative sentiments. He continued that it was hard now to predict the index movement. "The \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  happens because investors have temporarily lost their faith. Therefore, they choose to hold cash for safety. However, in principle our market fundamentals are still strong," he said yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 In the meantime, the rupiah exchange rate against the US dollar fell by 33 points to IDR9,493, the lowest in the past six months.   \par \par \uc2 Analyst at Optima Investama Rachman Untung added the index drop so far happened on a healthy level and had yet dragged down IHSG to 1,908.63 in August 2007, when the index was affected by the sub-prime mortgage crisis.   \par \par \uc2 However, the index drop yesterday triggered margin call, so that brokers providing financing facilities to investors were forced to sell their guarantee stocks. A broker at a foreign brokerage firm confided some stocks forced to sell were, among others,  \uc2 PT Aneka Tambang\uc2  Tbk, PT  \uc2 Barito Pacific\uc2  Tbk,  \uc2 PT Bumi Resources Tbk\uc2 , PT  \uc2 Bakrieland Development\uc2  Tbk, and  \uc2 PT Timah Tbk.\par \par \uc2 The margin facility provider made a force sell because the stock guarantee value had declined.   \par \par \uc2 According to the broker, the Indonesia Stock Exchange (BEI) could actually suspend stock trading yesterday to prevent the index from declining further, but the authority didn't do that.   \par \par \uc2 "Our SOP indeed has a mechanism to suspend trading, but we should also consider how the market will reach. I think the current situation doesn't need to make us suspend trading," viewed President Director of BEI Erry Firmansyah.   \par \par \uc2 Time to buy   \par \par \uc2 Head of Research at  \uc2 BNP Paribas\uc2  Ferry Wong, in his e-mail to investors, told it was the right time to buy the stocks of good companies with strong fundamentals.   \par \par \uc2 "We believe the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and market will be better when the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  plunges into recession. This is because the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and market are more independent In addition, Indonesia has relatively low interest rate to spur credit, provides \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  companies, and experiences strong CPO and coal prices," he argued.   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Japan's Nikkei 225 index fell by 5.7% to 12,573.05, which was the largest percentage drop in the past ten years. One day before, the index also declined by 3.9%.   \par \par \uc2 Despite the sluggish bourse, the Bank of Japan still maintains its interest rate at 0.5% and is optimistic its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  will still be able to grow, albeit lower than expected.   \par \par \uc2 In the meantime, the Shanghai index fell by 7.2%, the lowest level since August 2007. The stock index in Australia also plummeted by 7.1%, the largest drop in the past 20 years, while in Hong Kong the Hang Seng index dropped by 8.2% yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 In India, Minister of Finance P.Chidambaram asked investors not to panic after the trade in Mumbai was suspended by an hour following the decline of stocks by 10% in the early minutes of the trading. At yesterday afternoon, the Sensex declined by 6.2%.   \par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, some other bourses worldwide had slight rebound. Up to the publication of the news at 00.30 the Indonesian Western Time Zone (WIB), the Dow Jones index hit 11,993.3, or slightly rebounded from its opening. (Bisnis/rni/pul/wiw/mcd/gak/nom/bes/abr/03/06)   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020080123e41n00001\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Jakarta Prepares Measures to Deal with the Impacts of US Crisis   \b0\par\par\uc2 425 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 January 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Minister of Finance Sri Mulyani Indrawati stated the government was preparing several measures to anticipate worse situations in the Indonesian financial market following the widespread impacts of the sub-prime mortgage crisis in the US.   \par \par \uc2 She revealed the government was still discussing the measures with the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 "We are thinking about several alternatives since the situation has been changing rapidly. However, I cannot announce what the measures are right now," she said at a press conference at the Department of Finance yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 However, in term of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2 , she continued, the government would maintain the 2008 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  at 1.7% of GDP or worth IDR74 trillion. According to her, domestic conditions would be secure and Indonesia would be able to survive amidst shocks and the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recession.   \par \par \uc2 She promised to maintain \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , despite the fact it would be harder to do so this year due to higher turbulence risk. "Whatever the situation is, the government will still maintain \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  at 1.7%,"   \par \par \uc2 Sri Mulyani admitted market situation in 2008 would be far more difficult than in 2007. Therefore, she added, the government would not put more pressures on \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The risk of market shock this year, she inserted, would make market players tend to refrain themselves and this would certainly affect the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook in 2008.   \par \par \uc2 Maintain momentum   \par \par \uc2 At the same time, Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs Boediono asserted that domestic conditions would not be disturbed amidst global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  since the government would be able to maintain momentum.   \par \par \uc2 "Indonesia will not plunge into recession since our export commodities are still profitable. Indonesian export commodities prices are quite good and oil price has declined," he argued.   \par \par \uc2 Minister of Trade Mari Elka Pangestu explained that Indonesia, like any other members of WTO, had instruments to protect its domestic market from dumping, \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and safeguard policies. "We have anti-dumping and safeguard instruments. However, we cannot apply protection \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to our domestic market," she said.   \par \par \uc2 In addition, the Minister of Finance said she would not relocate energy \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to food \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 However, she added, the government would make discussion with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  under the Revised State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  mechanism if there were changes in the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The Minister of Finance also made her commitment to maintain the composition of foreign debts and loans. She told the government would boost revenues from VAT and income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , non-\b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  state revenues, and from state-owned enterprises dividends. (Bisnis/luz/bsi/dle)   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020080123e41n00002\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
